[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Welcome to the intermediate section of Rigging Isn\'t Scary. You\'re now climbing out of the Rigging Valley of Confusion. By carefully working through all three levels of the course, you\'ll gain solid experience with the fundamentals of'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rigging and develop a broad understanding of all main rigging features. This ensures that you will no longer feel lost when dealing with rigging because now you will have a map'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the entire area. There will be nothing that you truly do not understand. Of course, this will not be the end of your journey. In many ways, it\'s just the beginning of a far more exciting one where rigging is no longer'

[00:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'intimidating but exciting and enjoyable. We\'ll talk more about that at the end of this section. For now, let\'s focus on conquering the challenges of the intermediate rigging level. The goal of this level is to create a fairly'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'advanced rig. If you\'ve worked with Rigify or other professional rigs, our rig will be comparable. Compared to level two, it will feature an improved spine rig, more advanced twist'

[01:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanisms, IK/FK switching, limb isolation, an even better foot rig. Additionally, you\'ll learn new concepts like properties, drivers, shape keys,'

[01:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and how to apply them to your rig. We\'ll even create a shape key-based face rig. Thanks to our gradual and methodical progress, this section should not feel overwhelming. It will be slightly longer'

[01:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because complexity tends to grow, but we\'ll break it down into manageable chunks. Like the rest of the course, the intermediate lessons are designed to deepen your fundamental rigging'

[01:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'knowledge. That\'s what this course is all about. You\'ll notice that the videos in level three are longer than in levels one and two. That is because in order to optimize the release for YouTube, each'

[01:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'intermediate video actually contains three course chapters. That is a lot of information, so take breaks whenever you need, and as always, feel free to ask questions if you get stuck. Now, let\'s'

[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get started. We\'ll be rigging this character. You can get it from a download link in the description box down below. There are some license considerations, please read carefully, and I\'ll close this window. And for the'

[02:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'intermediate section, my Blender version is 4.3. If you\'re using Blender 4.1 and up, you should be able to follow this course 100%. As before, I\'ve tweaked my preferences,'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I\'ll be using tab for pie menu and extra shading pie menu items. Just like in level one and level three, we\'ll start by checking our model. In level one and level two, the character'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'was already prepared, and I just showed you the steps that I would take to make sure that everything is fine. At this level, however, I decided to start with a character that needs some attention, so that we can get actual practice with'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'preparing a character for rigging. And this is your first challenge. Pause the video and see if you can find everything that is wrong with this character and fix it. This character has props, which won\'t be'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the main focus of the course, but we\'ll use them later, so make sure to tweak them as well. The process of checking and fixing the character may take a while, but I promise you that this time is not wasted. A huge number of rigging'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'problems people ask me about are simply due to skipping the model check. Most of these issues could have been avoided by checking a few basics, such as the model size and orientation, applying'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transforms, and verifying symmetry. We haven\'t covered symmetry in detail yet, but it\'s coming up shortly. Okay, here is what I would do. I\'ll press shift S, cursor to world origin to move the'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cursor in the center of the world. Then from the front view, I can see that the character is sinking through the ground a little bit and it is not aligned with the center line. So, I\'ll grab it'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and align it with the center line as close as possible. I can switch to wireframe view and align the center of the character so that it overlaps with the blue Z axis'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that I see. Then zoom in on the feet, GZ and make them align with the floor. From the side view,'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll press GY and slide the character back a little bit so that the middle of the foot is in the center of the world. Now, I\'ll switch to the measure tool and'

[04:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'measure the character and it\'s about 3 m, which is almost double the normal human size. I\'ll measure about 1.8 m with the'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'measure tool and now I want to scale down the character. So, one thing you\'ll notice is that the origins of all the meshes are not in the center of the world. This is not a deal breaker. You'

[05:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can rig the character like this, although personally I like to set all origins in the center of the world. If you want to keep the origins exactly where they are, you can select everything,'

[05:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'switch your pivot to the 3D cursor and then scale down the character. Okay, but personally I\'ll press Ctrl A and apply all transforms and that will place all origins in the'

[05:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'center of the world. Then I can switch to bounding box center and because all origins are at the same place, all parts of the character will scale down from this point and they\'ll stay perfectly aligned.'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Because I scaled the character in object mode, it has unapplied scale. So, I\'ll press Ctrl A, all transforms again to apply the scale. Now, let\'s talk about symmetry for a'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'second. There are two types of symmetry. The character is generally symmetrical, meaning that it has two even legs, a fairly symmetrical body, and a symmetrical head. And even though the'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'arms are clearly different, they are about the same size. But, there is another type of symmetry, which I would call true symmetry, which means that for every vertex on the left side, there is an exact mirror on the'

[06:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right side. Having a character which is truly symmetrical makes rigging and especially weight painting a little bit easier. But, one of the goals of this section is to show you that rigging a slightly non-symmetrical character is'

[06:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not such a big deal. But, that said, I know that the head of the character and some of the head props are perfectly symmetrical. I made sure of that. And to make use of the symmetry, we have to make sure that the'

[06:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'center line is not just close, but exactly in the center of the world. So, here is how you can check for perfect symmetry and how to fix it if necessary. Select the head of the character, go to'

[07:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit mode, select all vertices with A, and enable the X symmetry option. I\'ll isolate the head. Press G and move the mouse. And now, if we had perfect symmetry, the center line'

[07:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the character should stay in the center and all of the left side vertices should move to the left and right side vertices to the right. Now, this is almost happening, aside from some vertices in the eye area. So, to fix'

[07:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this, keep all vertices selected and go to mesh, snap to symmetry. Now, when I press G, all vertices from the left and right move in their respective direction. So, this is perfect symmetry'

[07:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now. So, let\'s go to object mode, select the head, and do the exact same thing. Enable symmetry, move, and this seems to be fine already. But, if it wasn\'t, I would go to snap to'

[07:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'symmetry. The mask is fine as well, and the glasses also seem to be fine. So, snap to symmetry is a truly magical'

[08:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tool, but only use it when you\'re absolutely sure that the mesh is supposed to be symmetrical. If it wasn\'t, then Blender may find symmetry when there is none and actually mess things up. So, for example, I would'

[08:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'definitely not do mesh to symmetry on the body. The character is now ready for rigging.'

[08:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you have any doubts about your model check, I\'ll provide my verified model at this state, just in case, so that you can start with the same model I\'m using and get the same results. Now, I can go'

[08:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ahead and add the initial armature. Don\'t forget the best practice. Place the 3D cursor in the center of the world by pressing Shift S, cursor to world origin,'

[08:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then Shift A, armature. And do not move, rotate, or scale this armature in object mode. Moving and animating the finished rig in object mode is okay, but while rigging, just keep it right there'

[09:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the center. As always, go to the armature tab, enable in front, and let\'s go to edit mode. Now, we\'ll continue with another challenge. Create the base armature for this character,'

[09:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which will look like this. This should be really easy for you at this level. Keep in mind the techniques and best practices we learned in level two, Precise bone placement using anatomy'

[09:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'references as a guide. Pay attention to bone roll. Don\'t forget the slight bend of arms and legs. Some things may not be straightforward, but that\'s okay. We\'ll do it together as well. But as a hint,'

[09:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'since the left and right arm are different, align the bones to the right arm for now and symmetrize it. We\'ll tweak the left arm later in the course. We also know that the root is a feature'

[10:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of every rig, so we\'ll create it from the start. Also, parent your bones in a logical hierarchy and make sure the root is the top of that hierarchy. All right. First, I\'m going to hide the'

[10:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'props. We don\'t need them for now. And as always, I\'m going to use my default bone to build the spine. So, press G, Z and move it up and then scale it down. And then from the side view,'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m going to start aligning it. So, one way to do this is to align this one bone to the whole body. Then select it, right click, subdivide. And now let\'s see how many bones we\'re going to'

[10:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want for the spine of this particular character. I want to make the spine more flexible than the one in level two. So, I\'m going to give it five bones. So, I\'ll need four cuts. Now, the bottom two bones will represent'

[10:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the pelvis and one half of the so-called lumbar spine. And the remaining three bones will be the upper half of the lumbar spine and two bones for the chest.'

[11:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s name the bones right away. The bottom one will be pelvis.'

[11:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Spine one. Spine two. Chest one. And chest two. And I\'ll extrude the neck'

[11:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to just below ear and then the head bone straight up. From the front view, let\'s create a new'

[11:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bone. And align it with the shoulder area just like we did in level two. Usually I work on the left side first and then I symmetrize it to the right'

[11:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'side, but here we\'re going to favor the natural arm. So, I\'ll be working on the right side of the character first. Let\'s name this bone shoulder.r. Shift D and duplicate it.'

[12:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Scale it up to encompass the whole arm. Right click, subdivide. And let\'s align it from the top view as'

[12:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well. Here is the slight bend in the shoulder. And from the front view the arm is completely straight. Now, I\'m going to extrude the hand bone.'

[12:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And align it. And now let\'s create the finger bones. So, I\'ll grab the hand bone, shift D and'

[12:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'duplicate it. I\'ll use the volume snapping technique that I showed in level two. Switch snapping to volume. And what I actually like to do is to keep snapping disabled like this.'

[13:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then if I select one part of the bone, move it and hold control, snapping will be enabled while I hold control. And this is awesome because you can just keep snapping disabled and only activate'

[13:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it when you need it. So, again I\'ll select the end of this bone, hold control, and snap it at the end of the finger. Let\'s duplicate four bones for each'

[13:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finger, and snap them at the knuckles, and then at the tip of each finger. Check your bones from various angles to'

[13:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'make sure they\'re aligned correctly. Let\'s duplicate this bone and align it with the thumb, like this.'

[14:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, select all of your finger bones and the thumb, right click subdivide with two cuts. Select all of the middle phalanges, and move them slightly from the front'

[14:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'view to create this curvature of the fingers. But, also, let\'s carefully snap each joint where it belongs. So, for example, this joint should be'

[14:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aligned with this texture detail, because that is where the finger is supposed to bend. You can also enable wireframe, and that will give you another indication where the joints need to go. Okay, now the fingers are aligned with'

[15:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the joints, and we have a nice curvature, and as a finishing touch, you can use scaling to make these bones completely straight on this axis.'

[15:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, select all three bones of a finger, switch transformation to normal, enable the scale gizmo, and scale on the Z axis.'

[15:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then press zero and enter to make the bone completely straight. I\'m going to rotate it and move it slightly to align it perfectly. And I\'ll do the same for all fingers.'

[15:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'From the front view, I think I can move'

[15:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these knuckle joints slightly higher. At this level we\'ll also create palm bones. Palm bones are a subtle but still very important part of a nice hand rig.'

[16:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I\'ll grab the hand bone, shift D and duplicate it. Scale it down a bit and I\'ll make four copies of it.'

[16:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'These are a palm bones. So, I\'ll use the volume snapping technique to snap these bones inside the palm of the character. I\'ll make the hand bone a little bit'

[16:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'smaller because it is not as important when we have palm bones. And it also gets in the way. All the palm bones are now snapped'

[16:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inside the hand or the palm of the character. And each one is pointing towards one of the fingers. Now, let\'s name the arm bones.'

[17:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; I\'m going to name the palm bones palm 1'

[17:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '2 3 and 4 starting from the pinky towards the index finger. Under the armature tab, there is a handy'

[17:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'option to show the bone names in the viewport. I don\'t like having it on all the time, but you can enable it and check your bone names. My bone names look okay so far, so I\'ll'

[18:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disable the option. Let\'s create a new bone for the leg. In front view, I\'ll rotate it and align it roughly with the leg.'

[18:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then from left orthographic view, I\'ll make some additional adjustments. I\'m keeping anatomy in mind when'

[18:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aligning this point. I\'ll subdivide the bone, align the knee joint with the knee and give it a little bit of a bend. Extrude the foot'

[18:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the toe. And let\'s see what we have from the front view. I may want to move this toe a little bit to the side. This gives me the ideal leg alignment'

[18:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'straight from the front view and a slight bend in the knee. &gt;&gt; Let\'s name these bones.'

[19:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now I can symmetrize the bones by selecting everything, right click, symmetrize.'

[19:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here I\'m going to enable X symmetry and do the parenting. I\'ll parent the thigh to the pelvis. The shoulder to the second chest bone,'

[19:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keep offset. Upper arm to shoulder. Let\'s parent all palm bones to the hand bone. And then each finger to the palm bone'

[19:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'closest to it. And the thumb, I\'ll also parent to the closest palm bone. Check your parenting in pose mode.'

[20:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the left arm will need to be'

[20:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'adjusted because we have this mechanical arm, which is slightly different from the organic one. But that\'s okay, we\'ll keep these bones like this for now, and we\'ll make adjustments when we get to rigging the mechanical arm later in the'

[20:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'course. Let\'s go back to edit mode, add one more bone, call it root, rotate it, and I want to rotate around its head, so I\'ll switch to individual'

[20:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'origins, press R, type 90, and press enter. Yeah, I can scale down this bone a little bit and then parent'

[21:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the pelvis to the new root bone. Now the root bone moves all of the other bones. There wasn\'t a lot of new information in this video, but get ready because starting from the next one, we'

[21:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are diving straight into creating rig mechanisms. And they will be more advanced than what we did in level two. There will be plenty of fun challenges along the way, but as always, I\'ll be here to demonstrate and explain every'

[21:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'step and every decision in detail. Whenever you\'re ready, let\'s move on. It\'s going to be fun. The first mechanism we are going to work on will be the advanced twisting, but before that, let\'s quickly look at our'

[21:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'axis. Here I\'m going to zoom in and show you what my rig axis look like. And if your axis are different than mine, you can copy my axis. Again, you have to go to'

[22:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit mode, select any bone or many bones, press control R and roll the bones to adjust their axis. So if you need to adjust your axis to be exactly like mine,'

[22:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here I\'m zooming in on the hands. We may tweak the axis later in the course, but for now, this is what I have and it should be a good start. Okay, now to the twists. Until now, we'

[22:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of went with the flow. We created a basic skeleton that made sense based on our understanding of the character we are rigging and its anatomy. Then we noticed issues such as the candy wrapper'

[22:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effect on the wrist and we fixed them as we went along. Now that we have more experience, it\'s time to get more strategic with our rig creation. For example, we know that we are going to'

[22:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want twist bones. In level two, we used a single twist bone, which by itself was somewhat insufficient. So we had to use the preserve volume option to improve the lacking deformations. There is'

[23:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'nothing wrong with preserve volume, although I\'m not a fan of the bulging problems, even though we managed to fix them. On top of that, preserve volume cannot be exported out of Blender. So, if you\'re working on a game rig, it is'

[23:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not something you can rely on. Therefore, we want to create more complex twist mechanisms using multiple bones. This will be based on the simple twist mechanism that you already know. So, it will be only slightly more'

[23:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'complex. Now, the question is how many twist bones do we want? I want to save you the time and trouble of testing it yourself, and I\'ll give you this rule of thumb. One twist bone was obviously not enough.'

[23:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Two twist bones are still insufficient. With three bones, you\'re going to start to get nice deformations. Four twist bones is where we start to get really nice twisting deformations. Five twists'

[23:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will only look slightly better than four, so we are starting to get diminishing returns. And as you add even more than five bones, you will probably not be able to tell the difference. Of'

[24:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'course, these numbers are meant for an average human, such as our character. If you have a character with very long limbs, then more subdivisions may be beneficial. And also, in advanced'

[24:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rigging, the twist bones are also used for squash, stretch, and cartoony deformations. But anyway, for our character, we\'re going to go with four twist bones, which is optimal, in my'

[24:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opinion. So, we want to take the forearm and the upper arm and subdivide them into four bones, like this. So, I can select the bone, right click, subdivide,'

[24:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and give it three cuts, and that gives me the twist bones that I want. But this way, we lost our main lower arm bone. Working only with the subdivided bones can become a little bit abstract.'

[24:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, what we want is to keep our main bone, but also have these subdivided bones. So, let\'s undo. And so, of course, what we want is to'

[25:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'make a copy of this bone. And I have X axis mirror enabled, so I\'m making a copy of the opposite side as well. I\'m going to undo because the mechanical arm does not need twist bones.'

[25:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Disable X mirror, and now I\'m going to press shift D and duplicate this bone, right click to cancel the movement, right click again, subdivide, and give it three cuts.'

[25:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I can enable X-ray here to see my bones, or you can disable it, go to the object preferences, viewport display, and choose display as wire. This way your'

[25:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones will always be see-through, and this is a very useful and commonly used display mode for rigging. Now to the actual mechanism. As I said already, it will be based on the'

[25:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanism we built in level two. So, as a challenge, try to set up the same mechanism from level two only on our first twist bone. So, keep in mind the parenting, the constraints, and the'

[26:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraint options that we need to use. Feel free to watch the video from level two again, although ideally you should learn this mechanism by heart. Part of becoming better at rigging is building a library of mechanisms that you know. For'

[26:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one thing, you\'ll be able to reuse them really fast, but also by building this library, your mind may start to combine them in new and original ways without your conscious awareness.'

[26:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, so I want to parent this twist bone to the main lower arm bone. And actually, this makes sense for all of the twist bones. So, let\'s select them all. Shift select the main bone to make it'

[26:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'active, control P, keep offset. Then in pose mode, I\'ll hide the main bone, select the hand bone, shift select the first twist bone, control shift C, copy rotation.'

[27:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In the copy rotation options, I\'ll switch to local space and local space, and then control shift C again and use damped track. And this is a basic twist.'

[27:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, what do we need to do to set up the remaining twist bones? Currently, I have this first twist bone, which basically copies the Y rotation of the hand 100%. For the remaining bones, we basically'

[27:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want the same thing, except that there will be a falloff in this direction. So, the second bone will copy around 66%, third bone around 33%, and the fourth one zero or a very low number.'

[27:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I can set up the exact same constraint for the second bone. Select the hand, shift select the second twist bone, control shift C, copy'

[27:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotation, local space. By the way, you can click here and press S, and that will switch to local space, and W is world space. So, local space, local space, and also damped track.'

[28:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And to make this bone twist only 66% with the hand bone, we can adjust the influence slider here. 66% will be 0.66. Now, the first twist bone rotates fully'

[28:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with the hand, and the second one rotates a little bit less. I can set up the third and the fourth bone the same way, but there is a better way. I\'ll select the second twist bone and press control alt and C. This is a'

[28:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new shortcut, which removes all constraints from a bone. It only works in pose mode. Then I\'ll select all of these twist bones and lastly I\'ll select the first'

[28:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'twist bone which has the constraints. Then go to pose, constraints, copy constraints to selected bones. Now all selected bones will get the same constraint as the active bone and now'

[29:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all I have to do is go through each of these constraints. For the second twist bone I\'ll set influence to 0.66. Third bone 0.33. And for the first one I can set it all'

[29:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the way to zero. I can even delete this constraint or disable the eye icon, but I\'m going to set it to 0.1. So there will be a slight twisting but not a lot. I think especially since this character'

[29:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has a jacket, this will give us a very nice twisting effect. This is our twisting now. I think you can clearly see the falloff of the twist bones. But to actually test it, let\'s'

[29:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'apply automatic weights. I\'m going to press alt H, unhide this bone and I want to make it non-deforming. Because we now have these four bones along the length of the lower arm, we don\'t need the main bone. It will only'

[29:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be used for mechanisms. So in a second I\'m going to rename it. But for now let\'s go to object mode, select all meshes, shift select the rig, control P, automatic weights.'

[30:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to pose mode. Twist the hand. I\'ll disable overlays and check out the twisting.'

[30:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It is really nice and we are not even using preserve volume. Okay, let\'s take a second to rename these bones.'

[30:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I disabled the deformation of the main lower arm bone. So now it is an MCH bone, a mechanism bone which we talked about in level two. The twist bones, I\'m going to name lower'

[30:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'arm twist a number and dot R. Good. Now we can move to the twisting of'

[31:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the upper arm. Let\'s go to edit mode, select the upper arm bone, shift E to duplicate it, right click to cancel the movement, right click subdivide and give it three cuts,'

[31:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which means four new bones. The advanced twisting of the upper arm will also be based on the simple one we did in level two. So, again revise if you have to and make sure that you know and understand'

[31:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the simple twisting mechanism. As a challenge, implement the simple twisting mechanism to the first twist bone in the shoulder. For our shoulder twist bone in level'

[31:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two, we parented a single twist bone to the shoulder or clavicle bone. So, let\'s do this again. Control P or rather this bone was already parented because keep offset is grayed out.'

[31:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then we went to pose mode selected the main upper arm bone, shift selected the twist bone, control shift C, damp track. We set head tail to one so that the'

[32:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'twist bone points at the tail of the main bone. We then added a copy location constraint so that the twist bone moves with the main bone.'

[32:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But we had to adjust the order of these constraints to get a more stable rig behavior. Now let\'s hide the main bone and let\'s see what happens if we just copy this'

[32:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same setup to the remaining twist bones. Select all twist bones. Make sure the one that has the constraint is active and go to pose, constraints, copy constraints.'

[32:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Alt H and it kind of works. All of our twist bones rotate and move with the main bone. But they do not twist with it.'

[32:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Is this what we want? Let\'s apply weights and test it. I\'ll make the main upper arm bone non-deforming. Go to object mode.'

[33:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Select the jacket. Shift select the rig, control P automatic weights to recalculate the weights. Now for moving the arm up and down and'

[33:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back and forth, this looks okay. But when we twist the upper arm, this is not at all what we want. We have the entire upper arm completely'

[33:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'static and not twisting at all. What we really want is that the bone at the shoulder does not twist, but the remaining twist bones do need to twist progressively with the main bone. By'

[33:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'progressively, I mean that the second twist bone will twist slightly, the third one more, and the fourth one will fully twist with the main arm. Any ideas how we could accomplish this?'

[34:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Well, we could use copy rotation constraints so that the twist bones follow the main upper arm bone and play with the influence of the constraints to create a falloff from the elbow towards'

[34:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the shoulder. So select the main bone, shift select the last twist bone, control shift C copy rotation. And this one can have full influence.'

[34:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then set up the next twist bone, control shift C copy rotation, and set influence to 0.66 or so. Next one, 0.33.'

[34:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the last one we can leave without copy rotation, or we can give it copy rotation with a very low influence, such as 0.1 or so.'

[34:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if I twist the arm, we\'re getting the falloff twisting effect from the elbow towards the shoulder. And it is looking really good just with'

[35:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'automatic weights. And this setup works, and you can use it like this. But as usual in this course, I\'m trying to point out things that can help you figure out and understand better what is actually happening. So,'

[35:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s look at our constraints. We have this copy location constraint, which copies the position of the main upper arm bone. And that makes sense for'

[35:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this first twist bone, but the second twist bone has the exact same constraint. Yet, it doesn\'t go to this position. Any ideas why? Well, if I go to edit mode, these bones'

[35:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are parented and connected because we created them by right click and subdivide, which creates connected bones. So, connected parenting overrides the copy location constraint. These'

[35:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'twist bones are all connected to each other, so they cannot jump to the position of the copy location constraint. And that\'s totally fine. One thing you can do is just go to pose mode and'

[36:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'delete the copy location constraint for these three bones. But let\'s go to edit mode. I\'ll hide the main bone, select all of the twist bones, press Alt P, and choose disconnect bone. So, that'

[36:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will keep the parenting, but it will make it disconnected. Now, if I go to pose mode, all of the twist bones will jump to this position because now they can move based on the copy location constraint. Now, can you'

[36:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think of a way to keep this disconnected parenting, but still fix this? And I\'ll give you a hint. You can keep the constraints exactly as they are, but you need to tweak something in the copy'

[36:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'location constraint. Here is what we can do. I\'ll go to edit mode. We can make the copy location of each of these bones copy the location of the previous twist bone, and it has to copy its in'

[36:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'particular. So, let\'s go to pose mode. And now all of these bones are overlapping, so they\'re hard to select. A trick you can use is go to the armature tab and switch to rest'

[37:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'position. Now, all bones will be in their rest position regardless of constraints and so on. Now, I have this bone selected. I\'ll go to its constraints. And now I have to switch the target bone to be the previous twist bone,'

[37:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is currently named upper arm R.001. I\'m going to copy this name and paste it in here. And now I also need to switch the'

[37:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'head-tail slider to one. Actually, let\'s go back to pose position. And now as I slide the head-tail to one, you\'ll see how this bone goes to the position it is supposed to be in. So, if I click a couple of times, I'

[37:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'should be able to select the upper arm R.003, and I have to set its copy location constraint to point to the previous bone, which is 002. Slide head-tail to one.'

[37:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And finally, let\'s try to find 004 here and set its target to 003 and slide head-tail to one.'

[38:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, even though we had a simpler solution with the connected chain of bones, I wanted to show you this one because it is actually a basis for more complex setups, especially when you want'

[38:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to have squash and stretch and cartoony effects. So, I believe it will be useful to you anyway, and also it was a nice opportunity to dive deeper into the constraint settings. So, next we\'re going to go to the legs'

[38:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and set up the shin and the thigh in the exact same way. So, the shin setup will be exactly the same as the lower arm setup, and the thigh setup will be very similar to the upper arm setup. So, if'

[38:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you want a challenge, try to do it yourself. Okay, the setup is basically the same. So, let\'s do it as quickly as possible. I\'ll go to edit mode, select both of these bones, shift D and duplicate them,'

[39:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right click and subdivide them with three cuts. Therefore, the lower leg, I\'ll select all twist bones. Make sure that the main shin bone is'

[39:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'highlighted, control P, keep offset. Then in pose mode, hide the main bone, select the foot, shift select this twist bone, control shift C,'

[39:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'copy rotation, local space, and local space, and control shift C again, damp track. Then select the remaining twist bones, select the one that has the constraints,'

[39:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pose constraints, copy constraints. Let\'s set up the follow off. The second bone will have the copy rotation influence of 0.66. Next one, 0.33.'

[39:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the last one, a very, very low value. I\'m going to want almost no rotation. Now, for the thigh,'

[40:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s go to edit mode. I\'ll hide the main bone, select all twist bones, press alt P and disconnect bone so that we have the disconnected setup so that we have to set up copy location. Go to pose mode.'

[40:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can check the arm constraints they\'re the same. So we need copy location, damp track, and copy rotation. So let\'s set up copy location, damp track,'

[40:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'copy rotation. Okay, now for the copy location of the remaining twist bones, we have to set it up so that each bone copies the location of the previous twist bone. So let\'s select this bone, shift select'

[40:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the next one, control shift C copy location, and set head tail to one. Then same for the next two bones. Copy location head tail to one. And this bone and the last bone, control shift C copy location, head tail to one.'

[41:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now I want to set up damp track and copy rotation the same way as on the first bone. You can set it up manually, but if you go to edit preferences, get extensions, and ideally allow online'

[41:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
