[45:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Delete all bones. Alt H. And then I\'ll select all bones of the right leg. Right click and symmetrize them. And then I\'ll recalculate'

[45:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the weights by applying automatic weights again. And now we have working twists in the legs as well. Which will create very nice deformations'

[45:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'when twisting the leg. All right. That was quite a step up from the twist bones in level two. This kind of twisting is actually what you get in professional rigs. So, awesome work.'

[45:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Next, we are going to be working on a more advanced spine rig. In fact, it\'s going to have similar functionality to a Rigify spine rig. This spine rig will be slightly more advanced than what we did'

[46:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in level two, but it is still fairly simple. Compared to the twisting mechanisms we just did, the complexity is fairly low. Let\'s get into it. So, similar to level one, we want to'

[46:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create a separation between the upper arm of the spine and chest and the lower part of the torso, which can bend left and right and forward and back'

[46:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from this point. In the lower part of the torso, which again will bend and twist from this point, but in the inverted direction, so that the character can shimmy, twerk,'

[46:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and so on. Before I start building the mechanism, I may want to even out the length of these bones. I base their initial position on anatomical references, but as we discussed in level two, armature bones do not just'

[47:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'represent anatomical bones. They also affect the muscles and cloth and so on. And so, their influence tends to even out. So, I\'ll go over something like this.'

[47:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I feel like this point here should go a little bit lower. Ideally, you should place your main bones perfectly before starting to build the mechanisms, because once we have these twist bones'

[47:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and so on, moving parts of the rig becomes more difficult. But if you absolutely need to do it, you\'ll have to select all bones in the upper leg and switch to a pivot point like bounding box center and global transformations. And now I'

[47:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can lightly scale this bone and move it up and down. And I also want to symmetrize this change, so I\'ll enable X symmetry, press G lightly, and that will symmetrize the left side.'

[48:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, now this is almost perfect, but one of the bones is slightly offset. So, I could go to edit mode, select the whole'

[48:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lower leg, switch orientation to normal, enable scale. This is the same thing we did to straighten the fingers, and then I\'ll scale it on the X axis and press'

[48:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'zero and confirm. Now, these bones are perfectly straight again. And you can also squash on the Z axis just in case. And let\'s do the same for the upper leg. Okay, this was a little precision tip'

[48:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for tweaking complex rig parts. Although, ideally, you shouldn\'t do this and you should have everything laid out perfectly from the start. But, the world is not an ideal place. Now, let\'s focus on the spine. First,'

[48:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m going to create the mechanism for the lower part of the spine, which will be the most difficult part, but nothing to worry about. So, let\'s go to edit mode. And in level one, we had a single pelvis bone, so we'

[49:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just flipped it and used it in its flipped state. We could do the same here by selecting these bones and pressing Alt F to flip them. And again, we have to re-parent the'

[49:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones because the flipping messes with the parenting, but I\'m going to undo because I don\'t want to flip these bones. I want to keep them like this because this is a best practice. Even'

[49:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'though we\'re not building this rig specifically for games or another specific purpose, having the deform bones with this logical orientation is ideal for various purposes. So, instead, we\'ll select these bones,'

[49:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Shift D and duplicate them, and then press Alt F to flip the copies. And now we want these flipped bones to become our controls. So, the original deform bones need to move with them. If'

[50:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you want a challenge, try to do it yourself. The only tip I\'m going to give you is that it\'s not a complex setup. So, try to think of the simplest possible solution. Okay, let\'s go to edit mode, and all we'

[50:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have to do is parent each original bone to its flipped counterpart. Control P keep offset. And I select the pelvis, shift select the flipped pelvis, control P keep'

[50:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'offset. Now, in pose mode, we have the flipped bones controlling the original deform bones. Nice. I want to add one more level of automation on top of this, and let me hide the original bones to make'

[50:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this clearer. I want to add a control that rotates both of these bones, and as they rotate, they\'ll create a nice natural curve. Let\'s go to edit mode.'

[50:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Select the first flipped bone, shift D and duplicate it. I\'ll switch orientation to global, and pivot to individual origins, and then scale up this bone so that I'

[51:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can distinguish it. Then go to pose mode, select the new bone, shift select the first flipped bone, control shift C and choose copy rotation. And then again, select the new bone,'

[51:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shift select the second flipped bone, control shift C copy rotation. And we have to switch our copy rotation to local space and local space for both bones that we created.'

[51:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, when I rotate this new control bone, notice how it rotates the first bone, and then it also curves the second bone. Actually, I can do something else.'

[51:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Instead of using copy rotation on this bone, in edit mode, I\'m going to select it and shift select the new control bone, press control P and keep offset.'

[51:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And this gives us the same effect. The reason I decided to change the approach is that a bit later in the process, we\'ll add a main torso control. And with this setup, parenting the whole spine to'

[52:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the torso control will be simpler. So, what\'s happening is the first flip bone is rotating with the control bone, and the second flip bone is parented to the first bone, so it rotates with it, but'

[52:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it also gets copy rotation from the control bone, and so it rotates a little bit more, creating a little bit of a curve. And that is exactly what we wanted. One final tweak I\'ll do to this copy'

[52:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotation is to set mix to add, so that I can also rotate this bone manually. So, I can rotate the main control, and then choose this one, and also tweak its rotation manually.'

[52:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I can also do this for this bone. Now, we are going to create almost the same curving mechanism for the upper three bones.'

[53:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, in edit mode, select the spine two bone, shift E and duplicate it. Make it slightly bigger. Parent spine two to the new bone that we just created.'

[53:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then, in pose mode, select the new bone that will be our control, shift select chest one, control shift C copy rotation, make it local space and local space,'

[53:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mix to add. And I want the exact same constraint on chest two, so let\'s select chest two, shift select chest one, pose, constraints'

[53:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'copy constraints to selected bones. Now this control bone curves the upper spine. So in edit mode, I\'m going to make it even bigger.'

[53:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The size doesn\'t really matter, but by making it this long I\'m indicating that it controls these three bones. Once we give it a custom shape, it will be even clearer, but for now this is'

[54:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also very nice. If you find that the spine curves too much with this curving mechanism, you can reduce the influence of the copy rotation constraints. This will be a'

[54:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'matter of taste. Personally, this looks good to me, so I\'ll keep it like this. So now I can rotate this left and right front and back and even twist it, and'

[54:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
