[55:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there are many ways to achieve the exact same effect. At the end of the day, if it works, it\'s good. But, if you can make the setup simpler and easier to understand, that\'s a plus because, for'

[55:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example, it can make troubleshooting your own rig easier. Now, to set up the parenting, I just need to select the top and bottom spine control, shift select the new torso bone, and parent with keep'

[55:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'offset. And that will give me the torso control, the lower body control, and the upper body control,'

[56:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as well as individual chest and spine controls. If you have used Rigify, for example, you just created something that functionally is very similar to the Rigify spine.'

[56:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I\'m going to name this bone torso. This bone will be the chest control, so for now, I\'ll name it chest control. Later, I may change these names.'

[56:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And this one will be the hips control. And the individual bones in the hips'

[56:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'area, I\'ll name hips one and hips two. And I\'ll press Alt H to unhide the hidden bones. I also noticed that I accidentally named'

[57:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this bone just MCH. It should be MCH upper arm.r. Also, after parenting the body bones to the torso bone, I lost the root function'

[57:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the root bone. It just doesn\'t do anything, so I have to go to edit mode, select the torso, shift select the root, control P keep offset. And now again, it moves the whole'

[57:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character. It doesn\'t move the mechanical arm, that is a width issue and we\'re going to work on it. Do not worry about it. As always, take a moment to congratulate yourself for your progress. You just created a nice, fairly advanced, and'

[57:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'highly practical spine rig. Next, we\'re moving on to something completely new. We\'ll make all limbs of this character work in both IK and FK mode, and we\'ll set up an automated IK FK switching'

[57:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanism. In level one and two, we kept the legs exclusively in IK and arms only in FK. This setup works well because it\'s'

[58:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simple to create and covers about 80% of basic animation needs. But now we are taking a step toward a more professional rig. In the next few videos, we are'

[58:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to build a solid IK FK switching mechanism. This means you won\'t be stuck with just one or the other. You\'ll be able to switch each arm or leg to whichever mode fits your animation best.'

[58:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If you\'re wondering why IK FK switching is so useful, first is a general rule, IK is ideal for animations where the legs or arms are attached or interacting'

[58:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with something. FK, on the other hand, works best when the limbs are swinging freely. Here are a few examples. For many common animations such as standing,'

[58:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'walking, running, even dancing and so on, the legs will often interact with the ground, so IK is necessary. The arms will mostly swing freely, so FK is a'

[59:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'good choice. For animations such as pushing, pulling, or picking something up, the arms will interact with the object being pushed or pulled, so IK arms will be essential. If the character'

[59:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is swinging on a bar, IK for the arms is amazing here because it makes it easy to show the character holding onto the bar. And for the legs, FK gives you a natural'

[59:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'swinging motion. Finally, if the character is flying through the air, both the arms and legs are moving freely, so FK is your best option. So, IK FK switching is essential in a'

[59:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'professional rig. Fortunately, it is not difficult to implement. The main challenge is that we need to create and constrain a couple of overlapping chains of bones, which can get confusing if you'

[60:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'try to rush it. That\'s why we\'ll take it slow, step-by-step, until it all makes sense. Now, I\'m going to save my file here and start a new general file.'

[60:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This will allow me to demonstrate an important technique that we\'ll be using in the IK FK setup. If you have any objects in your scene, delete them and then create a new armature.'

[60:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to edit mode, select the default bone, and make two copies of it. Now, I\'ll go to pose mode,'

[60:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the first copy, shift-select the first bone, and press control shift C to add a new constraint. And I\'ll use the copy transforms constraint. We already included copy transforms in our list of'

[60:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basic constraints, but we haven\'t used it so far. You can think of copy transforms as copy location, copy rotation, and copy scale all packed into a single constraint. Using copy'

[61:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'location, copy rotation, and copy scale individually will give you more control, but if you just want one bone to follow the transforms of another bone, the simplest and quickest way is copy transforms. So, I\'ll click on it.'

[61:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now it will look as if our original bone disappeared. You probably understand that it has not disappeared, but because of copy transforms, it moved to the location of the target'

[61:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bone because copy transforms also includes copy location. If I play with the influence of this copy transforms constraint, you\'ll see'

[61:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how the constrained bone goes to its initial location and the stronger the influence, the more it moves towards the target bone. We also want to constrain the first bone to this other bone, so it will have two'

[62:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'copy transforms constraints. But before that, let\'s learn how to work with overlapping bones, such as what we have here because overlapping bones are very common in advanced rigs. Go to the'

[62:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'armature tab, viewport display, and switch display as to B-Bone. B-Bone means bendy bones. Bendy bones are an amazing advanced rigging feature, which we won\'t be using'

[62:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in this intermediate section, but B-Bone display mode is useful regardless because I can select all bones and press control alt shift and S and change their thickness.'

[62:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I can also select an individual bone and press control alt shift and S and change the thickness only of the selected bone. Now, if I switch to wireframe shading, I\'ll be able to see the individual bones'

[62:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even though they\'re perfectly overlapping. This thickness is only for display purposes and it doesn\'t change the function of the bone. In octahedral mode, the bones are still'

[63:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'perfectly overlapping. If I switch to any shading other than wire, the bones will not be transparent, so I could go to the object properties, viewport display,'

[63:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and switch the display of the armature object to wire. Now, this armature will always be see-through regardless of other display settings. Okay, so now I want to add another constraint to this thinner bone,'

[63:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the target will be this bone. So, let\'s select it and press control alt shift and S and make it slightly thicker. And now I want to shift select the'

[63:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thinner bone, but unfortunately, I won\'t be able to do it directly. This is something that is being worked on, and hopefully, in one of the next Blender versions, you\'ll be able to just select this bone that you can clearly see, but'

[63:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'currently, it is not possible. So, here are a few workarounds. One is to select this bone and press control shift C and make it thicker than the other one. Now, I can easily shift select it.'

[64:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Another way, which I use very often, is to simply hide this bone that gets in the way. Now, I can shift select my bone. Yet another way is to point at the overlapping bones and press alt shift'

[64:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and click. And now I can select any overlapping bone from this menu. And here, I know that I want bone. Okay, yet another way is to switch to rest position, which displays the bones in their unconstrained state. Now, the'

[64:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones are not really overlapping, so I can select this one and then easily shift select the other one. So, hopefully, all of these workarounds will not be necessary very soon, but until then, they are essential, so keep them'

[64:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in mind. With these bones selected, I\'ll press control shift C and copy transforms, and then switch back to pose position. Back in pose position, the constraints will now take effect,'

[65:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and now the constraint bone is fully controlled by this bone. So, I can move, rotate, or even scale it, and the constrained bone will move,'

[65:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotate, and scale with it. And that is because we have these two copy transforms constraints one over the other, and they are evaluated top to bottom, so the second one overrides the first one. If I switch the influence of'

[65:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the second copy transforms to zero, now the first one takes effect, which means that this bone is fully controlling my constrained bone. And this setup will become the basis for'

[65:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our IK/FK switch. In edit mode, I\'m going to move this bone in the center, so that it overlaps with the constrained bone, and this one also'

[65:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'roughly in the same area. I\'ll press control, alt, shift, and S to make it slightly thicker. And now by just playing with the'

[66:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'influence of the second copy transforms, I can determine which bone controls the constrained bone. And if you imagine that, for example, this is the IK, and this is the FK, this will be the basis'

[66:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for our IK/FK switch. Of course, the final mechanism will be applied on a chain of multiple bones, but as long as you understand this basic principle, you can keep going, and you should be able'

[66:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to understand the full setup. So, let\'s go back to the edge shoulder rig and set it up. Now, for the actual IK/FK switching setup. As a little overview, what we want to do is create two copies of this'

[66:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'entire leg chain, one for FK, and one for IK. And we\'re going to constrain each bone of the original chain to the FK chain, and then also to the IK chain, using copy transforms, just like in the'

[67:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simple example we just saw. And by turning the bottom constraint of each bone on and off, we\'ll switch between IK and FK mode. And of course, we don\'t want to switch each constraint'

[67:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'manually, so we\'ll use something called properties and drivers to automate the whole setup and make it easy to use. Okay, so in edit mode, select all of'

[67:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these bones, thigh, shin, foot, and toe. Press shift D. And actually, I\'ll cancel and press control Z, and I want to turn off symmetry. I\'ll only work on the right side and then I\'ll symmetrize the left'

[67:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'side. So, shift D, make sure you\'re in global mode, so X, and then I\'ll type minus 0.3 on the numpad. Then enter to confirm, and that moved this new chain of bones exactly 0.3'

[67:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'units, or minus 0.3, on the X axis. I did this because later I\'ll want to bring this chain back to its original position, overlapping exactly with the original bones. So, when I want to do'

[68:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this, I\'ll move it again on the X axis and type 0.3 on the numpad, and that will bring it back to this position. Now, I\'ll cancel this. Now, I want to rename this new chain of bones. This will be my FK chain, so I\'ll'

[68:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rename it to thigh FK.R. Shin FK.R.'

[68:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Foot FK.R. And toe FK.R. Now, I\'ll select everything, and I want another chain for the IK. So again, I\'ll'

[68:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'press shift D, X, and minus 0.3, and enter to confirm. And now I want to rename my IK chain, and for that, let\'s use batch rename, which you can find'

[68:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'under edit, batch rename, or the shortcut is control F2. Switch your type to bones, and then using find replace, find FK, and replace it by IK.'

[69:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, now these bones are renamed to thigh IK.R, but they also have this 001 suffix. So, select all bones, again control F2,'

[69:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and find .001, and replace it with nothing. Just leave this blank, press okay, and that will effectively delete the 001 suffix. So, batch rename is extremely important in'

[69:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rigging. Keep it in mind. Okay, next we want to constrain our original chain to the FK chain. So, what I want to do is first select the thigh of the FK chain.'

[69:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then shift select the original thigh, and press control shift C, copy transforms. And now the leg will jump to this position because of the copy transforms constraint. So, let\'s go to the armature tab, and switch to rest'

[70:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'position, which is the technique that I just showed you. And now I can keep constraining, and my bones will not jump around. So, constrain the shin bones, then the foot bones,'

[70:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and finally the toe bones. And then do the same for the IK chain. So, select the thigh in the IK chain, shift select the original thigh, control shift C, copy transforms. Then the shins,'

[70:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then the feet, and finally the toes. Now, if I switch to pose position, the whole leg will be overlapping with the IK chain. Because the second copy transforms'

[70:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraint is pointing to the IK chain. Actually, let\'s go back to rest position, and name our constraints. This is something we haven\'t done so far, but it can be done.'

[71:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'For example, I can name this copy transforms FK and the lower one IK. And this is another level of organization, which can help you make sense of your own rig later because things may seem obvious as you do them, but then later'

[71:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you may be asking yourself, "What did I even do here?" So, any type of organization is good. Let\'s do this for all of these bones. First one is FK and second constraint is IK.'

[71:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now I want to bring the IK and FK chain back to their original position, but before that, let\'s place them on'

[71:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'individual collections because once they\'re overlapping, they can be hard to select. So, select all FK bones, press M, new bone collection, and let\'s just call it FK for now.'

[71:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the IK chain, M, new collection, call it IK, and click create. Now I can easily hide and unhide these collections.'

[72:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now in edit mode, select the FK chain, press GX and 0.3 and enter to confirm. Then the IK chain and then press GX and 0.6.'

[72:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'By the way, if you didn\'t use exact values when moving these bones, here is what you could do. I\'ll undo. Slash to isolate the rig. Switch snapping to vertex.'

[72:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'G to grab this bone, then hold control and point it to the original leg chain and then click to confirm. This will also place it at the exact position I want. And slash to go back out of local'

[72:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mode. Now, we have these overlapping bones, so let\'s use a B-bone display to make things clearer. I\'ll switch to B-bones and all bones are pretty thick by default, so select'

[72:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything and press control alt shift and S and let\'s make them reasonably thick. Now I\'m going to start the IK chain and make it much thicker.'

[73:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then remove the star and enable it for the FK chain and control alt shift and S to make this chain thicker, but if I enable IK as well, I want it to be slightly thinner'

[73:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than the IK chain. Okay? Now I\'ll un-start everything and disable IK and FK. Now if I switch back to octahedral, I\'ll'

[73:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the thigh, shin, foot and toe. These are the original ones and then back to B-bone, I\'ll press control alt shift and S and make them slightly thicker.'

[73:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So now the twist bones are the thinnest. The original leg chain is slightly thicker. The FK chain is slightly thicker than the original chain and IK'

[74:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chain is slightly thicker than FK chain. So I understand that this can still be a little bit confusing, but it\'s much better than having everything overlapping. Right, so now in pose mode'

[74:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the IK copy transforms is at the bottom and I\'ll have to switch to pose position and now my IK chain is controlling the leg.'

[74:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If I un-star my default bones, I\'ll be able to select all of the original leg bones, go to constraints and if I hold alt and reduce the influence of copy'

[74:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transforms IK that will disable this constraint and allow the FK constraint to take effect. So, now the FK chain is controlling the'

[74:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leg. Now, at this point, both the FK chain and the IK chain are actually FK chains. So, this is obviously not the full setup. What we need to do is now focus on the IK chain and set up the IK exactly as we did in level one and level'

[75:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two. So, I\'ll press Alt R here to reset the IK chain and I\'ll start it to focus on it. I\'ll go to edit mode, select this connection at the ankle. If you want to switch back to octahedral,'

[75:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s fine at this point. Then press E Y to extrude a new bone, select it, Alt P, clear parent, name it IK target.r.'

[75:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to pose mode, select the target, shift select the shin. And by the way, we have an even faster way to set up IK, and that is the shortcut Shift and I. So, IK is the super constraint and it'

[75:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has its own shortcut. Press two active bone. Go to your constraints, set chain length to two.'

[75:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Extrude the pole target, unparent it, G Y to move it away, name it'

[76:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leg IK pole. r, and I\'ll have to name this bone leg IK target.r. Then I set the pole target,'

[76:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pole angle to 90. Parent the pole to the target. And now we have our basic IK setup.'

[76:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if I start the default bones, I can select all of the main bones.'

[76:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Alt and click on the influence and set it to one. If alt and clicking doesn\'t work for you, you can set it to one and then right click, copy to selected. Now, the IK chain will be controlling'

[77:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the main chain, which means that when I move the IK controls, the leg will be controlled by it. There is still work to be done on the individual IK and FK mechanisms, but the basic switch now works. So, let\'s review'

[77:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what we did. It\'s important that everything we did so far is clear before moving on. So, let me clear the transforms.'

[77:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I\'ll switch to B bones so that I can see the full mechanism and start the default bones. So, here we have the initial or main leg chain, and the twist bones are fully'

[77:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parented and constrained to it. Then, we created two copies of the main leg chain, one for FK and another one for IK.'

[77:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And we constrained the main leg chain to both of them. So, the main chain itself will never be animated directly. It will be controlled either by the FK or the IK controls.'

[78:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The cool thing is the twisting mechanism will work in both IK and FK mode because it is controlled by the main leg chain, and the main chain is controlled either by IK or FK. This gives us a really'

[78:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clean separation between the different parts or levels of the rig. So, if you we to tweak the a we\'ll focus on the main chain and the twist bones and tweak things on this level.'

[78:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then we could focus separately on the IK chain and create whatever additional automations or mechanisms that we need to, such as the advanced foot setup that we\'ll work on shortly. And everything'

[78:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will work just fine as long as we keep these four main bones intact because the main leg chain is constrained to them. And similarly, we could focus on the FK'

[79:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and add more mechanisms there. We\'ll add the so-called limb isolation mechanism. But before that, let\'s make the IK FK switching more user-friendly. The obvious problem now is that in order'

[79:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to switch to IK and FK mode, we have to tweak this influence slider on four bones. And that is just for one leg. We also want to have an IK FK'

[79:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'switch on both legs and both arms. And that makes switching quite tedious. And a slightly deeper issue is that this main leg chain is MCH, which means that it\'s supposed to be hidden from the'

[79:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'animator. We are going to resolve this by learning the basics of two new rigging tools, custom properties and drivers. This will allow us to create an automation which switches between IK and FK with a single slider. Let\'s start'

[80:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with custom properties because they\'re really not that difficult. A custom property in Blender is just a number, just a custom value that you can use for whatever you like. In our case, we are'

[80:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to create a custom property and we are going to tell Blender that this influence value on all four bones is equal to that custom value. So, by just tweaking one value, all four constraints'

[80:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will be affected. Another benefit of a custom property is that it can appear in the interface, so we\'ll be able to highway these MCH bones. The main thing that can be confusing'

[80:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about custom properties is that they appear in different contexts or different modes. So, for example, we have object mode, edit mode, and pose mode for our armature. So, even if I don\'t go to object mode, I can go to the'

[80:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'object properties and at the bottom I\'m going to find custom properties. And these are custom properties for the object level of this armature. I\'ll click the new button and that gives me a'

[81:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'new property called prop. I can click on the gear icon and for now I\'ll just change the name to object prop and press okay.'

[81:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There are no custom properties under physics or constraints. These are the object constraints. Then under data, you will find custom properties. So, let\'s press new here. Click the gear icon and let\'s name this'

[81:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'data prop. Then under bone, we again have custom properties. And the important part here is that when I create a new property at this level, it'

[81:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will be attached to the active bone. If I select any other bone, it won\'t be there. If I select my MCH_thigh.R again, here I have my new property. And'

[81:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something else that you have to keep in mind is this is now a pose bone property. If I go to edit mode, I\'ll have the exact same bone selected, but no custom property. So, I\'ll click new again to get a new property on the'

[82:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit mode level. I\'ll click on the gear icon and I\'ll call it edit prop. And then back in pose mode, I\'ll edit the name of my'

[82:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pose property to pose prop. And these are the main levels on which you can create a custom property. Now, if I go to the N panel, item tab, properties, I\'ll see my pose property'

[82:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exposed here. If I go to edit mode, I\'ll have the edit property exposed. And in object mode, I\'ll see the object property. The data property does not really get exposed. We'

[82:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do want an exposed property to make our rig more user-friendly. So, that means that the data property is out of the question, so I\'m going to delete it. So, now we have the object, pose, and'

[82:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit property. We animate in pose mode, so having to switch to edit mode in order to tweak the IK/FK switching does not sound like a good idea. It\'s not logical. So, let\'s go to the bone tab in edit mode and delete the edit property.'

[83:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, we are left with the pose and object properties. Switching to object mode in order to change the properties is not such a bad idea because we could easily expose all'

[83:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'properties for this rig on the object level. So, this could work, especially with the pie menu, because it makes switching between the modes so easy, but personally, I would like to just stay in'

[83:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pose mode while animating. So, I\'ll delete the object property. And now we are just left with the pose property. Now, the pose property needs to be attached to a specific bone, and the NCH'

[83:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thigh is not a good candidate because it is supposed to be hidden. So, I\'ll have to delete this property and think of a better bone for it. Using the root bone could be a good idea'

[84:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because the root bone is always exposed, but it may not be very intuitive. So, here is what we are going to do. Let\'s go to edit mode, create a new bone, scale it down, and make it a little bit thinner,'

[84:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and place it to the side of the character. F2 and name it rig settings. So, this will be a special bone, which will contain all of our custom properties. It will act as a menu for'

[84:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the rig. Later, we\'ll give it a special shape, so that it\'s easily recognizable as a settings button. Now, let\'s go to pose mode, and give it a custom property.'

[84:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Click on the gears icon, and let\'s name the property right leg IK FK. The property type is float, which is'

[84:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically a decimal. The influence slider on the constraints is also float, so that\'s perfect. The default value is one. This should work, although we can tweak it if necessary. The minimum value is zero, and maximum'

[85:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is one. This is also perfect, because the influence slider also goes from zero to one. The rest of the settings, you can ignore for now, and press okay. Now, you have a really good'

[85:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understanding of custom properties. Personally, it took me a while to figure out the difference between the various contexts in which properties can exist. So, I\'m happy to simplify it for you. Just figure out the most logical'

[85:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'context, or mode, for your needs, and add the property there. It\'s as simple as that. The property itself is just a value, regardless of the context. Now, we can move on to drivers. Drivers can'

[85:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be complicated, but on a basic level, they create connections between different values in your scene. Anywhere in your scene where you see numbers, such as the XYZ location, rotation'

[85:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'values, scale values, and so on and so forth, these values can be connected through drivers. So, as a quick example, let\'s go to edit mode, shift A, and create a new bone. This will be just a'

[86:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'simple temporary bone for demonstration. Then, I\'ll press shift D, and duplicate the bone, and go to pose mode. Then I\'ll select the first bone and right-click on one of its values. Let\'s'

[86:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'say the Y location and choose copy as new driver. Then go to the other bone and let\'s right-click on its Y value. And now I can paste the driver.'

[86:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is probably the easiest and simplest way to create a driver relationship. The value turned purple, which means that it contains a driver or it is being driven. So the Y value of'

[86:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the first bone is driving the Y value of the second bone, which means that if I grab this bone and move it on its Y value, the driven bone will also move on its Y axis.'

[86:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What\'s interesting about driven values is that once the driver is applied, you can no longer tweak this value manually. So I can try to change this value any way I like, but I won\'t be able to.'

[87:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We connected the Y value to the Y value, but that was arbitrary. I can right-click on the existing driver and delete it. Then I\'ll right-click on the Z location axis and paste the same'

[87:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'driver I copied earlier into it. So now the Y location of this bone will drive the Z location of the other bone. I can also paste the same driver into'

[87:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'another axis. Let\'s say the Y location again. Now the Y location of this bone drives both the Y and Z location of the other bone.'

[87:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Or I could delete this and paste the driver into the X rotation. So now moving this bone will rotate the other bone.'

[88:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'As you can see, drivers can be used to automate things in the rig just like constraints. In fact, a long time ago Blender did not have this powerful set of constraints, so drivers were the only way to automate your rig. Now, copy'

[88:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'driver, paste driver is the easiest way to add a driver, but it is a little bit limited. It just gives us a one-to-one relationship between two values, which will kind of be enough for our example,'

[88:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but I want to get a little bit deeper here into drivers because this is meant to be a fundamentals course and I want to give you the fundamentals of drivers, which will take you closer to being a professional rigger.'

[88:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, let me delete this driver. I\'ll split a window here and I\'ll switch this window here to drivers.'

[88:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Look at that. We have a whole interface just for drivers. Now, with this bone selected, I can right-click on any value, let\'s say the Y value, and simply add driver. This gives me a little temporary'

[89:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interface, which will disappear easily, but if we look at our drivers interface and click on the new driver that was added we now have this whole interface, which allows us to tweak our drivers. And here'

[89:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the side panel, I\'ll switch to drivers. There is a lot going on in the driver editor. We have a graph similar to the animation curves.'

[89:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We have a modifiers tab, menus, and so on. We may come back to some of these other elements later in the course, but for now we\'ll ignore them and just focus on the driver settings area because it is the most fundamental one.'

[89:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Type is set to scripted expression and that is the most common and powerful mode because it gives you access to this expression field. In it, you can type any mathematical expression that you'

[90:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like and it will be evaluated and that will be the result of the driver. By default, Blender gives us var, which is a variable. It\'s a variable defined down here. Actually, it is not fully defined'

[90:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yet. We\'ll define it in a second. And then we have plus zero. So, plus zero obviously doesn\'t do anything, but Blender is trying to indicate that here we can use variables, numbers, and'

[90:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mathematical expressions. So, we could also type var multiplied by 2.5. 4 minus var.'

[90:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Var divided by 4.7 and so and so forth. All sorts of mathematical expressions are fine. So, for now I\'ll delete the numbers and just leave var. Var is just a random'

[90:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'name that I defined here in this field and then I can use it in the expression. To finish the setup of this variable, I need to tell it which object it is based on. So, I\'ll choose the armature and just like with the target of'

[91:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraints, we now get access to a specific bone in this armature. So, I want to use this bone here, which is named just bone. Now, the driven bone moved and that is because the driver is now fully set up'

[91:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it is based on the X world location of this bone. The X world location is this here and so this bone moved on its Y location, which is driven,'

[91:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'by the same amount. To set this custom driver exactly as we set it up with the copy paste workflow earlier, I have to switch to Y location and local space.'

[91:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now again, moving this bone on its local Y axis will move the driven bone on its Y axis. But now that we have full access to the driver expression, I can do fun things'

[91:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like multiply the variable by two, for example. Now, moving this bone on its Y axis will move the other bone twice as much. Or I can'

[92:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'divide it by two, so the driven bone will move only half as much. This variable has a type, and by default it\'s set to transform channel, which gives you access to the location,'

[92:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotation, and scale transforms of the object, and also different spaces. Again, you\'ll mostly use world space and local space, just like in constraints. There are other types for the variable,'

[92:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but again, most of the time you\'ll be using either transform channel or single property. So, let\'s switch to single property. It\'s very important to understand the workflow here. So, again,'

[92:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you have to set the object where the property will be found. Again, it will be our armature. Now, let\'s go to the first bone that we\'re using here. Right click on its Y axis, and choose copy data path. Go back to'

[93:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the driven bone, and paste what you just copied into the path field. Now, again, if I move this bone on the Y axis,'

[93:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the other bone will move according to the expression that I set here. So, by using single property, I can also affect transform channels, but choosing transform channel specifically will also allow you to use world space and'

[93:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transform space, so it is a little bit more versatile. But, back to single property, I can now go to my rig settings bone, right click on the custom property, and copy its data path.'

[93:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to the driven bone, and paste this value here. And now, I can control the position of this bone with this custom value. Now, once you understand this, it should'

[93:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be very easy to automate IK/FK switch. I\'ll go to edit mode and delete these temporary bones. Go back to pose mode. Select the MCH bone.'

[94:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to my bone constraints. Right click on influence. Add a driver. In the driver editor, I now have this underlying driver. It means that data is'

[94:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'missing. Uh so, I can just delete it. That was our test driver. And now we\'ll go to our influence driver. Let\'s set the expression to just far. Type to single property.'

[94:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to our settings bone. Right click on the property. Copy the data path. Go back to our drivers. Select the prop as armature. And paste the path we just copied.'

[94:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if I set my IK/FK setting to zero, and go back to my constraints, you\'ll see that influence is also set to zero. Okay? The number always corresponds.'

[95:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Instead of setting up all remaining drivers manually, you can right click on this one, which is already set up. Choose copy driver. Go to the next bone. Right click on the influence.'

[95:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Paste driver. Go to next one. Paste driver. And next one, paste driver. Now, having this value between zero and'

[95:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one is kind of pointless. I want to set it either to zero or to one. I\'ll move the IK a little bit and the FK'

[95:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a little bit. And so, a value of one currently means IK and a value of zero means FK. But our name says IK FK, which kind of'

[95:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'suggests that zero would be IK. We could tweak the driver expression to account for this, but probably the easiest way is to just go to the bone tab,'

[96:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit the property and just change the name to FK IK. Now, because we changed the name, the'

[96:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'driver will stop working. So, let\'s right click on this, copy data path, star only the default bones, and paste the path to update it. So,'

[96:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll have to do this for all bones. Okay. Now, it\'s fully updated. And one means IK,'

[96:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and zero means FK. Nice work. IK FK switching, properties, and drivers are essential rigging tools. So, we just took a major step forward.'

[97:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In the next two videos, we\'ll keep building important mechanisms like a fully automated foot rig, FK limb isolation, and an advanced hand rig. In this section, we are going to focus'

[97:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on improving the IK part of the leg rig. The main focus will be on enhancing the foot mechanism. As always in this course, we are building on what we already learned. So, there will be'

[97:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'plenty of things you are already familiar with, but we are taking things to the next level, adding more complexity, automation, and just an extra layer of coolness. Let\'s dive in. Okay, I\'m going to close the driver'

[97:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'editor for now. And since I want to work on the IK mechanism, I\'ll make sure that the FK IK value is set to one. This way I\'m in IK mode and I\'ll be able to test whatever changes I make to the'

[98:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'IK mechanism. I\'ll reset the rig and hide all bones except for the IK and also highlight the IK collection so that any new bones I may add will be added to'

[98:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this collection. I guess we can set display to octahedral because there are no overlapping bones. And now let\'s finish setting up the foot bone as we did in level one and level'

[98:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two. You should be familiar with this so try to do it yourself. Okay, so again the problem is that when we move the torso down, the foot sinks into the ground.'

[98:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So we solve this by going to edit mode and parenting the foot bone to the IK target bone. Keep offset. Now we want to fix the fact that we can'

[99:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disconnect the foot from the shin. And we do that by selecting the shin, shift selecting the foot, control shift C, copy location and setting head tail to one.'

[99:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Before we move on to the next topic, here is something that I want to mention at this level. I have prepared a special scene and I have set up my IK constraint as usual but I haven\'t set up the foot'

[99:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'yet so it sinks through the ground. If I select the foot bone and go to the bone tab, expand relations, here I can see information about the parenting of this'

[99:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bone and also there are special settings for the parenting. So for example, here we can enable connected or disconnected parenting. Which is the same as pressing Alt P and'

[99:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'disconnect bone. And there are other settings. One of them is inherit rotation. So if I disable it and then go to pose mode and then try to move the spine, you\'ll'

[100:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see that the sinking of the foot is actually fixed. And if I move the spine up, the foot doesn\'t disconnect. So it may seem like a one-click solution to this problem. But if I select the root'

[100:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and rotate it, you\'ll see that this foot is not rotating with the whole rig. And the idea of the root bone is that it just moves and offsets the whole rig. This is because disabling this inherit rotation'

[100:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'setting makes the foot bone ignore the rotation not only of its direct parent, but from the entire hierarchy all the way down to the root bone. So while it'

[100:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'may seem like a really nice, quick, and simple solution, it has really important negative consequences. I\'m mentioning this because you may see this in other tutorials and so I wanted to warn you'

[100:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'why this is not a good idea. So enable inherit rotation and in general don\'t touch this area too much until you really know what you\'re doing. Okay, back to our main tutorial.'

[101:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Next we\'re going to create pivots for our foot system. This will be basically the same as in level two except that we\'ll have two more pivots on each side of the foot. So this may be a little bit'

[101:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'difficult, but save your file and give it a try. It will work in the exact same way. It\'s just two more pivots that you need to parent. Okay, let\'s go to edit mode'

[101:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and add our pivots. In level two we extruded the pivots. I\'m going to cancel this and undo because that created existing parenting and then parenting everything together was a little bit difficult. So, this time'

[101:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'instead, I\'m going to select this point here and press shift S cursor to selected and then just press shift A to add a new bone. With individual origins, scale it down. And this will be my toe pivot. And'

[101:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually, I don\'t want it exactly at the bone. I want to align it with the geometry. So, like this at the tip of the foot. Press F2 and name this bone foot'

[102:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pivot toe.r. Then I can press slash to isolate. Select this bone, shift D and duplicate it.'

[102:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Set snapping to vertex. Keep snapping disabled. G to grab the bone and hold control to snap it at the foot. And let\'s rename this pivot to pivot foot.r.'

[102:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then I\'ll go out of local mode. Shift D and I\'ll place this bone at the heel and rename it to pivot heel.'

[102:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then from the front view I\'ll duplicate the foot pivot and place it on the inside edge of the foot and name it'

[103:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'foot pivot inside. Shift D and place it on the outside and rename this to pivot outside.'

[103:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Actually, foot pivot foot may be a little bit weird, so let\'s rename this to foot pivot ball.r.'

[103:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now again, these pivots are just pivots for the IK. So, what we want to do is parent the IK to it and because a bone can have only one parent, we\'ll do'

[103:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our consecutive parenting. And now we have more bones, so the ball, toe, and heel will be as before. Then the heel will be parented to the inside pivot and inside pivot to outside'

[103:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pivot. All of these pivot bones are not parented to anything, so we shouldn\'t have any parenting issues like in level two.'

[104:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, let\'s parent the IK target to the ball, ball to toe, toe to heel, heel to inside,'

[104:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and inside to outside. Now the heel raises the heel. This bone raises the foot from the toes. This one bends from the inside,'

[104:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then from the outside. Now we need one more pivot at the ankle itself. So, again, let\'s go to edit mode, shift D and duplicate this bone.'

[104:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Scale it up with individual origins. I\'ll press alt P and clear any existing parenting. And then I\'ll parent the outside pivot because currently it is the topmost'

[104:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pivot to the new bone. Control P, keep offset. Now this new bone moves the whole setup. And the pivots act as individual pivots.'

[105:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The original IK target will now be an MCH bone because it is not meant to be animated manually anymore. And the new control that we created'

[105:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will get the normal leg IK target name. One thing that we haven\'t set up yet is'

[105:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the behavior of the ball roll. We want the toe to stay straight when rotating from this point. So, let\'s go to edit mode. I have my 3D cursor exactly here, so press shift A again and add a new bone.'

[105:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Scale it down and if you remember, we solved this by setting a dump truck constraint on the toe targeting this bone.'

[105:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And again, if you remember, we made a copy of the toe which is automated and the original toe stays unautomated and parented to this new bone.'

[106:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, let\'s parent the original toe to the new copy we created. Control P, keep offset. And let me name this MCH toe IK helper'

[106:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because it is meant to stay automated and not be animated directly. So, in pose mode, I\'ll hide the original toe. Select this bone which will be toe target'

[106:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '.R Then shift select the MCH toe. Control shift C, dump truck. Now, the toe stays straight, but I can select the original toe and offset and'

[106:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'animate it manually. There is one thing that we still need to do. If I rotate this bone the toe target should rotate with it. So, all we have to do'

[107:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is go to edit mode and parent the toe target to the toe pivot. Control P, keep offset. Let me reset the rig.'

[107:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And so far, we did almost the same as in level two except that we added two more pivot bones. Now, we\'re going to do something actually new, and it\'s going to be very'

[107:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cool and make this foot rig a lot more user-friendly. So, in the previous chapter, we already had this problem that if I rotate on the toes, the heel stays behind.'

[107:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, technically, I can still rotate on the heel, but I\'m not supposed to because now this heel pivot is not really at the heel, and so it doesn\'t really fulfill its purpose. The reason this works is that once I'

[107:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'raise the foot on the toes, I\'m not really supposed to rotate it on its heel. That doesn\'t make any physical sense. So, the setup works because each pivot'

[108:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is meant to be used individually and not combined with each other. However, by having all of these bones exposed, we make it possible for the animator to do something that is not realistic. So, now'

[108:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'ll add one single control bone that will control four of our pivots. Only the ball pivot will stay unautomated for now. Let\'s go to edit mode,'

[108:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I\'ll select my heel bone, shift D and duplicate it, and scale it up. And this will be our foot roll control. So, I\'ll press F2 and name this bone foot_roll.r.'

[108:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I want this new control bone to rotate my pivots. Which constraint can I use for that? Of course, copy rotation. So, let\'s'

[108:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the roll, shift select the heel pivot, control shift C copy rotation. And let\'s try to set things up only for this bone, and then the rest will just fall into place for the remaining three'

[109:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones. For target and owner, I\'ll switch to local space and local space. Now, when I rotate the foot roll, the'

[109:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'heel bone rotates with it. That\'s nice, but it rotates with it fully. I only want it to rotate on the X axis. I\'m in local mode here, and I can see that this axis is the X axis.'

[109:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I could disable Y and Z. Now, the heel bone will not react when I rotate the control left and right. But, it still rotates forward, which I'

[109:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t want. So, we need another constraint. And it\'s a constraint that we haven\'t used so far, but take a look at the list of constraints and see if you can figure out which one it is.'

[110:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It is limit rotation. Limit rotation, as the name suggests, allows us to control how much a bone is able to rotate. By the way, limit'

[110:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotation does not have a target. It\'s a constraint that just acts on its own on the bone that it is applied to. And that makes sense because we are just limiting the rotation values of the constraint'

[110:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bone. I\'ll switch owner to local space because what I care for is limiting the local X axis of this bone. So, let\'s enable limit X. And now we have a min and max value.'

[110:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s go to our roll bone and look at the rotation values. And as always in Blender, the default mode is set to quaternion. Here, switching to Euler will make things much'

[110:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'easier for us because it gives us these clean X, Y, and Z axis. The pivot bone can stay in quaternions because it is constrained, so this mode doesn\'t matter that much.'

[111:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s play with the X value. And giving the roll bone negative X values rotates backwards. So, for the limit rotation constraint,'

[111:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll leave max to zero. So, this bone won\'t be able to rotate forward. And I\'ll set minimum to minus 90 or so, which will allow it to rotate backwards.'

[111:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Select the roll bone. Rotate it back, and the heel pivot will rotate with it. But, if I rotate it forward, the heel pivot will stop, and it will do nothing.'

[111:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, this is perfect. It already works because we disabled the Y and Z axis. So, even if I rotate the control bone left and right, the heel doesn\'t react. Alternatively,'

[111:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can also enable Y and Z limit rotation, and just leave all values to zero, and then you could enable Y and Z axis, and the setup will still work.'

[112:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m just mentioning this quickly hoping that it will give you additional understanding into how constraints work and how they combine together. To set up your remaining three pivots, we\'ll need almost the same constraint'

[112:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'setup, except that we\'ll need to tweak the values on the limit rotation constraint. So, let\'s hide the control. Select the remaining three pivots. Shift select the heel pivot.'

[112:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Pose. Constraints. Copy constraints to give these pivots the exact same constraints. And alt H to unhide the control. Now, the toe pivot needs to do the'

[112:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opposite of the heel pivot. So, its minimum needs to be zero, which will prevent it from rotating backwards. And its maximum should be positive 90, which will allow it to rotate forward.'

[113:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And Y and Z will all be set to zero. Okay, and that is exactly what happens. Rotating this control forward now raises the foot from the toes, backwards from'

[113:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the foot. And now this doesn\'t work for two reasons. One is that the outside and inside bones are not fully set up with their limit rotation constraint.'

[113:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And another is that we most likely have a circular dependency. Let\'s go to edit mode. Select this roll bone. Go to the bone tab, relations. And because I copied this bone'

[113:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from the foot heel, it kept the same parent. The parent can be verified here under relations. So, the problem is that the foot roll bone is parented to the inside pivot bone. At the same time, the inside'

[113:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pivot bone has a copy rotation constraint, which has the foot roll bone as a target. And this is a circular dependency. Resolving dependency loops is not optional. You have to do it right'

[114:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'away because they may cause parts of your rig to behave unpredictably, making your rig unusable. Here we can solve this problem by just removing the parent of the foot roll bone. So, Alt P, clear'

[114:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parent. And the problem will be almost fixed. We still have a slightly weird behavior, and that\'s because the heel is parented'

[114:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the outside. And the limit rotation of this bone is still not set up correctly. So, it rotates backwards with the control, and then it moves its child. So, let\'s set up limit rotation on the'

[114:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inside. We don\'t want this bone to rotate backwards and forward at all. So, I\'ll set limit X minimum and maximum to zero. You could also disable the X axis in copy rotation.'

[115:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And we want this bone to rotate on the Z axis. So, negative Z rotates in this direction. Therefore, I have to set'

[115:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'limit rotation minimum Z to minus 90 and max will stay to zero so that this bone cannot rotate in this direction. Okay, so we are almost there.'

[115:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All we have to do is set up the outside bone, set limit X to zero zero and limit Z to zero to positive 90. Okay, now rotating the roll bone in each'

[115:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'direction only affects one single pivot bone at a time. So, all of these pivot bones will now become MCH and I\'ll be able to just hide'

[116:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them. And control the foot roll with this single control. But, I\'ll still have the ball as a manual control.'

[116:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, let\'s name these bones MCH dash This toe target is also MCH.'

[116:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And at this point, I guess we can start organizing our MCH bones in an MCH collection. &gt;&gt; so that we can hide bones that we don\'t'

[117:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really want to see. Later in the course, we\'ll do even better organization, but this should work for now. So now we have this really nice foot'

[117:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'control. Actually, after some testing, I see that I need to parent my foot roll to the IK target. This way the foot roll will move with the IK target, which makes more sense.'

[117:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And something else I noticed earlier is that I haven\'t parented the IK target to the root. So let\'s do that. Shift select the root, control P, keep'

[117:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'offset. Let\'s stay on the topic of IK for just one more minute, and we\'ll learn some'

[117:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'advanced rigging tools. I\'ll hide the main bones and select my IK shin. Go to the bone tab and find the inverse kinematics section. So every bone has special inverse'

[118:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kinematics settings. The settings we\'ll focus on here are the axis locks. So I\'m in local orientations, and if I enable the rotation gizmo, I can see that the lower leg bends on the X axis.'

[118:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'A realistic shin bone is not supposed to bend sideways or spin on its own axis. And so we could lock the Y and Z axis, and that will make the behavior of the'

[118:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leg slightly more realistic. If I move the IK and disable Y and especially Z, you\'ll see how the leg change its orientation to something that is not really'

[118:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'realistic, so I may have to tweak it with the pole target. That is why we are locking these axes. Although, of course, if you have a cartoony character, you may want to unlock these axes and achieve more'

[119:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cartoony deformations. And you may be asking, can\'t we just lock these rotation axes or couldn\'t we use the limit rotation constraint that we just used on the foot setup? And the'

[119:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quick answer is no. IK will disregard these settings. So, you may start to notice that even though IK is one of the constraints, it\'s a little bit special. In technical terms, IK is always'

[119:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'evaluated last. So, the constraint stack rules are slightly different for the IK constraint. And that is why we have these special IK settings.'

[119:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I think we managed to learn a lot about IK. So, let\'s move on to the next video where we\'ll create a completely new FK mechanism. It\'s an important isolation. First, let\'s see what it is and why it\'s'

[119:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'useful. I\'m going to unhide my main bones and I want to switch IK FK to zero so that I\'m in FK mode since I\'ll be working on the'

[120:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'FK mechanism. I\'ll also hide the IK collection and unhide the FK. So, in our rig right now, if I rotate any of the torso controls, the FK arms and legs just come along for'

[120:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the ride. They just rotate with the torso. With limb isolation, we can make the arms and legs keep their orientation while the body rotates. The easiest way to simulate this is to select an arm,'

[120:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for example, this upper arm and go to the bone tab and as in the previous video, I\'m going to disable inherit rotation just temporarily. I\'ll do it for this arm,'

[120:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this leg, and also for the thigh FK.R. Now, if I rotate the torso, notice the arms and legs keeping their orientation.'

[121:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'When I move the torso, they still move along, but they ignore the rotation of the torso. As it turns out, animators like this behavior a lot. They like it so much that many animators may prefer'

[121:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this to be the default behavior of their rig. And therefore, we are going to implement this behavior, but we are going to make it switchable, so that the user of the rig can choose whether the limbs should follow the body or not.'

[121:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'First, let\'s re-enable inherit rotation. Just like with IK, we cannot use it because it completely disables rotation from all parents, including the root, so'

[121:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it will cause as many problems as it solves. In here, you may have overlapping bones. Make sure that you have selected thigh FK.R. and enable inherit rotation.'

[121:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s do some really quick rig organization. I want to mainly focus on the FK bones, but I also want the torso controls to be visible, so that I can test my'

[122:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanism. So, let\'s select these three main torso controls, press M, create a new collection, call it torso controls,'

[122:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'press okay, and disable this general bones collection. Now, we\'ll create the isolation mechanism, and I\'m going to show you two ways to do it. The first one will use'

[122:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'less bones. It is slightly less convoluted, and most importantly, it will allow us to use and learn some new settings, which we haven\'t touched so far, which will also lead to better'

[122:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understanding of bone orientations. Okay, in edit mode, I\'m going to create a copy of the thigh FK bone. And with individual origins, I\'m going'

[122:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to scale it down. If I switch to B-Bone mode, I can press control shift and S to make this bone larger so that it\'s easier to select for parenting and constraints.'

[123:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll also make these bones a little bit thicker to distinguish them from the other bones in the spine. Okay, so now this new bone, which I\'ll'

[123:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'call MCH_thigh_FK.R for now, this bone was copied from the original FK thigh, so it is still parented to the pelvis bone.'

[123:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And so it will move with the hips. Now, as a little challenge, try to think of a way to change the relationship of'

[123:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the main thigh FK bone to the bones in this area. You can use parenting and constraints, and make it so it follows the rotation of this new bone we created so that when I rotate the spine, it will'

[123:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'move with it, but it will not follow its rotation so that we achieve this limb isolation effect. As always, it\'s okay to fail these exercises, but as long as you give it'

[124:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some honest effort, you will gain a lot more from this course than someone who just clicks where I click. Okay, so we can use a copy location constraint.'

[124:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So I can select this new bone, shift select the FK bone, control shift C copy location. And now if I test it, the main thigh bone is still rotating fully with the body. And that\'s because this bone is'

[124:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'still parented to the pelvis bone, which is not visible, but it\'s right here. So, what we need to do is go to edit mode, press Alt P, and clear the parent. Now, this bone will not have any parent, but it is constrained to this bone with'

[124:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'copy location. And there we go. This is the effect we\'re looking for. And we can still rotate this bone manually, which is important, but now we lost the default behavior of the leg'

[125:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotating with the body. But we can get this back easily by giving this FK bone a copy rotation constraint. Let\'s select the new bone, shift select the main FK bone, control shift C, copy'

[125:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotation. Now, we can have the default FK behavior, or if we disable the copy rotation, we have the isolated behavior. Nice, but we still have a problem.'

[125:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'When we enable copy rotation, we can no longer manually rotate this leg. One way we fix this in the challenge of level two was to set replace to add. Unfortunately, that doesn\'t work well'

[125:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with world space orientations. So, I can try switching to local space. Now, I can rotate the bone manually, but for some reason it is not following the orientation of this bone,'

[125:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even though copy rotation is active. Feel free to stop and think why that is for a minute or two. The reason this bone is not copying the'

[126:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotation of this bone is because the target is set to local space. Local space really means the local rotation of the bone, which means the amount this bone is rotated by itself and not by its parent.'

[126:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'As you can see, when I rotate the target bone itself, then the leg FK bone does rotate. So, what we can do is change the target from local space to local with parent.'

[126:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, this setup will start considering the rotation of the parent of this bone, and the FK bone will be oriented to'

[126:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that. And this setup is the simplest solution to this problem. Now, we are going to move to the slightly more complex setup, and the only reason is that in all honesty, I don\'t usually use these mix modes much, especially not'

[126:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'deep in the rig like this. While my guess is that this will work perfectly fine, I\'m just slightly worried that there might be some gotcha, and the rig won\'t work correctly in a very specific situation. So, we are going to add just'

[127:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one additional bone and create a setup that I have used a lot, and I\'m very confident in. We are going to use a technique that we already used in level two. I called it'

[127:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraint plus child technique. So, we want to create one more bone here, and we are going to offset these constraints onto that bone, and then just parent'

[127:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the main FK bone to that new bone. If you feel like it, give it a try. Okay, in edit mode, I\'ll create a copy of this bone, make it slightly longer and slightly thinner.'

[127:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I want to set it up exactly as I set up the main FK thigh, which means that I have to clear its parent. Then, in pose mode, I\'m going to select this bone,'

[128:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shift select the new bone, control shift C, and give it copy location, and then one more time and give it copy rotation. And we\'ll leave both of these constraints using world space for target and owner.'

[128:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'World space is highly reliable. It means that for copy location, this bone will always perfectly copy the location of the other one. And the rotation will always perfectly copy the rotation of'

[128:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the other bone. Now, for the main thigh FK bone, we want to remove the existing constraints. Instead of clicking the X button here one by one, we can also press control alt and C, and that removes all'

[128:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraints from all selected bones. Then, in edit mode, I just need to parent this bone to our newest bone, which now holds the constraints. Control P, keep offset.'

[128:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, when I rotate the pelvis, the leg rotates with it. That is because the copy rotation constraint is enabled. When I disable it, I get the isolated effect. But, whether copy rotation is on'

[129:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or off, doesn\'t matter. I can always manually animate and pose this thigh bone because it is simply parented to the constraint bone, and parenting does not impose any'

[129:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'limitations on the movement, rotation, or scale of the bone. So, that is the full setup, almost. This will work perfectly unless'

[129:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you decide to do some sort of scaling of your rig. Let\'s select the root and press S to scale it. And notice the weird scaling, or rather the lack of scaling in some parts of the right leg.'

[129:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That is because this bone here is now disconnected from the whole hierarchy, and it just uses copy location and copy rotation to follow the location and rotation of this bone. So, scaling is'

[130:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ignored. So, to fix this, all we have to do is select this bone, shift select the bone that has the constraints, control shift C, add a copy scale constraint.'

[130:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now rescaling will work just fine. &gt;&gt; Okay, now you definitely have a solid'

[130:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'isolation setup that will work in any situation. What we still need though is a custom property so that we can switch the isolation on and off depending on our preferences.'

[130:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So select the rig settings bone, go to the bone tab, custom properties, and add a new property. In the settings, I\'m going to call it right leg,'

[130:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I\'m going to call it follow, which is a common naming convention that you\'ll see in other rigs as well, such as Rigify, for example. Default value, min, and max are all fine. Steps, I'

[131:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'guess we can also set to one just like for the IK/FK switch. And press okay. Then right click on this new custom value, choose copy data path. I\'ll hide the bones collection.'

[131:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to my constrained bone. Go to constraints. Right click on influence, and choose add driver. Now I can try to tweak the driver in this window here, but as soon as I move'

[131:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'away, it will disappear. So we could again split the screen and have a driver editor, but another way you can do it is right click and choose open driver editor.'

[131:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And this will give me this temporary window that I can use. By the way, right click and edit driver will give you this very flimsy window, which is nice if you want to do a quick change. For more serious work, you can use the'

[131:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'floating driver editor. And if you\'re working a lot on drivers, then split the screen and create a dedicated driver editor. For my expression, I want it to be just'

[132:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'var, so it is equal to this thing that I\'m going to set up right now. The object is going to be the armature, and actually I need to switch to single property. Here armature is already set up, and'

[132:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then in the path field, I\'m going to paste the data path that I copied from my custom property. Now the default behavior is that the leg'

[132:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'follows the body. But if I switch follow to zero, it will stop following and will see the isolated behavior.'

[132:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I\'ll keep this as a default for now, and this is the full setup. Now let me just check if I can give better names to these bones. This bone can be MCH'

[133:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thigh follow.r because it determines whether the follow option is on or off. And this can be'

[133:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'MCH thigh parent FK.r because it kind of acts as the topmost parent in this hierarchy. Now if I switch to octahedral,'

[133:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll see all of these overlapping bones in this area. And even if I disable the main bones, we have these three overlapping bones here. And this is very common in'

[133:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rigging. The more complex the rig, the more of these overlapping bones you\'re going to have, and it can get pretty crazy with four or five or six overlapping bones in here. I\'m trying to keep this to a minimum in'

[133:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this course, but I also want to at least mentally prepare you for the future of advanced rigging. The way we keep track of all of these overlapping bones and all of the many bones in our rig is through clear naming, varying the size'

[134:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of these bones, and using thickness in B bone mode. And last but not least, organizing the bones into collections according to their functionality.'

[134:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Nice work implementing this completely new mechanism. Limb isolation can be used in many places. The arm actually benefits from this feature the most. We now have the right leg fully set up'

[134:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with nice mechanisms on both the IK and FK chains as well as an IK FK switch. Of course, we want the same on the left leg, which luckily is as simple as'

[134:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'symmetrizing the right leg. We\'ll also want the same mechanisms on the arm. Again, we are in luck because the setup will be 99% the same as on the leg. So, it\'s crucial that you understand the leg'

[134:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'setup before moving forward. So, let\'s symmetrize this whole right leg. I\'ll unhide all of my collections. Press Alt H to unhide any hidden bones,'

[135:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then go to edit mode and again press Alt H just in case anything is hidden. And now because we may have changed some names on the right side while working on the mechanisms, I\'m going to delete the'

[135:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'whole left leg and then symmetrize the whole right leg. This is usually the most problem-free approach. However, I\'m going to go on a little aside as I sometimes do, but I promise you that the'

[135:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only reason I\'m doing this is because it is important and it\'s something that can save you a lot of time and frustration. So, I want to select and delete all of these bones on the left leg. I\'ll use circle selection here with C.'

[135:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Check if everything is selected and now I can delete the bones. Currently, my X symmetry is disabled, but let\'s say that it was enabled. I\'ll enable it, press X,'

[136:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and delete the bones. Now, because of X symmetry, some of the bones that did exist on both sides were deleted on the right side. Which, of course, I didn\'t want. So,'

[136:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this may seem like not a big deal. I can just press control Z and then disable symmetry and delete again. All seems fine, except if I go to pose mode and hide these bones,'

[136:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you may notice that my twist bones are not green, which means that they don\'t have constraints. They used to have constraints. That is what created the twisting mechanisms, but the constraints are gone. Crazy, right? So, what'

[136:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happened was when I deleted these bones in edit mode and then I press control Z, that restored the bones, but any properties and constraints on these bones were deleted. So, this is a crazy'

[136:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'behavior of Blender\'s undo system and it hasn\'t been fixed in more than 15 years. I hope it will be fixed, but until then, you have to know about it and you have to keep it in mind. So, anytime you'

[137:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'delete bones and you realize that you actually didn\'t want to delete them, don\'t just press control Z once, press it as many times as you need. So, I\'ll keep pressing undo until before deleting these bones.'

[137:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then, I\'ll go to pose mode, hide these bones and you\'ll see that the constraints are back. So, again, after deleting bones by accident, undo more than once and check if the constraints'

[137:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and properties are back. And under edit preferences, system, I would advise you to crank up the undo steps to the maximum of 256, which should give you enough undo steps'

[137:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for most cases. Okay, special segment over. Now, we can delete the left leg. I\'ll go to edit mode, make sure that X symmetry is off. Press C for circle select and select all'

[138:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones on the left leg. X to delete them. Then I\'ll hide the root bone and select everything on the right leg. Right click and symmetrize.'

[138:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now we have the whole leg and all mechanisms symmetrized, but there is still some work to do. I\'ll start the main bones collection. Select the thigh for example, go to constraints'

[138:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and the driver from the influence of the copy transforms IK constraint is not there. Okay, on the right side we do have it, but on the symmetrized side we don\'t. Unfortunately, Blender does not'

[138:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'symmetrize drivers. But we can restore them easily. First I\'m going to copy this driver that I already have on the bones on the left side. Here is something that was added'

[138:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in Blender 4.2 and can save you some time. I\'ll select all left leg bones and then shift select the right thigh because it has this driver that I want. So I could copy this driver and then go'

[139:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back and paste it on all of the bones, but in 4.2 and later I can also right click and choose copy driver to selected. And now this automatically pasted this'

[139:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'driver in all selected bones. This is probably based on the constraint name here. So if your names are different, then it may not have worked. If you\'re using an older version of Blender or this simply didn\'t work for'

[139:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you, then of course you can still use copy driver and then paste driver. Okay, so now if I unhide my IK controls, I\'ll start the IK'

[139:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collection and try to move the IK controls. The leg is not reacting. That is because the FK/IK value is set to zero, which is FK. If I set it to one,'

[139:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then my IK will be active. However, this is supposed to be the property for the right leg. So, we have to add a new property. Let\'s select the settings bone, go to the bone tab,'

[140:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scroll down, and add a new property. I\'ll enable the properties for the right leg FK IK and copy the name. And then, for the new property, paste this name and just'

[140:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'replace right with left and change step to one. And press okay. Now we have a new property. So, I could copy the data path, but I don\'t'

[140:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'necessarily have to. I\'ll hide the IK collection and select all of these bones that have the driver. Go to constraints, right-click,'

[140:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open driver editor. And because I have all of these bones selected, in the drivers editor, I\'ll see the influence driver of all four bones. So, I can just click on each individual one,'

[141:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go to the path, and replace right with left. Okay, now that this is working, I\'ll copy the entire thing'

[141:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then paste it for the remaining influence drivers. Okay, if anything is wrong with what you'

[141:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'entered in the path field, let\'s say I have a typo here, the field will become red, which indicates that there is a problem. So, I just need to fix this typo, and it will work again.'

[141:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All right, so now we have an IK FK switch for the left leg as well. Okay, all set up in the legs. Let\'s unhide all bones, select'

[141:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything, alt R, alt G, alt S to reset the rig. And now we can focus on all the mechanisms of the arm. Again, I\'ll be working on the right arm. So, let\'s go to edit mode.'

[142:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I have X symmetry disabled. I\'ll only work on the right side. So, I\'ll select the upper arm, lower arm, and hand. And now again, I want to duplicate this'

[142:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'arm and offset it up or sideways. And so, I\'ll switch orientations to global. With global orientation, I can just press shift D and then Z to move the bones only up in world space, and then'

[142:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
