[160:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The control bone now does rotate the finger, but remember that we want to scale this bone to curl the finger. And with this setup, the control now scales the finger.'

[161:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, that\'s not going to work. Let\'s go back to edit mode. Select the base finger bone and re-parent it to the palm bone. So, what constraint could be used to'

[161:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'make the base bone rotate with the control bone, but ignore the scale? Sure. Of course, copy rotation. Select the control, shift select bone, control shift C, copy rotation.'

[161:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I can rotate the control bone, and I can scale it without affecting the size of the finger. We still may want to offset this bone'

[161:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'manually, so I\'ll switch mix to add. And local space to local space. Now, I can also manually rotate the finger.'

[161:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And when I move this control, it doesn\'t move the finger. This can be fine depending on what you want out of your rig. So, if you want to keep things realistic and not be able to move the finger, then you can just lock the location axis here, and then moving the'

[162:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finger will become impossible. But, if you want to enable slightly unrealistic effects, then you can select the control, shift select the base finger, and add a copy location constraint.'

[162:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I can also move the finger with the control. And scaling is still ignored. Now, we have to set up curling the finger when we scale the bone. Based on the things we have learned so far, what'

[162:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'could we use to create this automation? Think about it for a minute. Okay, if you thought of drivers, you would be correct based on what you know. This automation can, of course, be done'

[162:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with drivers. Ultimately, we are going to use something else, but let\'s practice setting up this driver and let\'s see why it is not the ideal solution. The rotation axis we want to automate is'

[163:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the Z axis. Our fingers are in quaternion mode, which makes setting up this driver a little bit more difficult. So, let\'s switch all finger bones to Euler. In a later video, we are going to have a special chapter all about setting'

[163:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up quaternions and Euler\'s, but for now, we\'ll just select all of these bones. Switch the active one to XYZ Euler, right click and choose copy to selected. Now, all bones should be in XYZ Euler'

[163:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and that will be good for now. Now, select the middle phalange of the pinky, right click on Z rotation and add a driver. Right click and open driver editor.'

[163:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Set expression to var, object to armature. The bone that we want is our pinky control, which is pinky.r. And we want to use its scale. We have X,'

[164:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Y, and Z scale and it really doesn\'t matter which one we choose because we are going to be scaling the whole bone. So, I\'ll just choose X scale. Now, our mechanism starts to kind of'

[164:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work, but the finger is already curled when the control is not scaled. That\'s because the default scale value is one. And if you\'re wondering why this bone rotates this much just based on a'

[164:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'value of one, it\'s because these values are calculated in something called radians and one radian is equal to 57 degrees,'

[164:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which we can clearly see here. Now, since the default value of scale is one, we could just change our expression to one minus var, so that at the default scale of one,'

[164:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the bone will be rotated 0°. And now our mechanism works. It is kind of slow, so if you want to make it faster, you can change the expression by placing'

[165:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the existing expression in parentheses and multiplying it by two. Okay, now this curling feels good. So, I could'

[165:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'copy this driver and paste it into the Z rotation axis of the last phalange. Now we have the curling mechanism. So,'

[165:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the only problem with this is that after setting up a driver, I cannot rotate this bone manually. The driven property is entirely automated. And for this setup, I want to be able to also manually rotate the bones. Of course, we'

[165:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can use a variation of our constraint plus parent technique. We can call it driven bone plus parent, but that means that I have to add overlapping bones again, which I want to avoid as much as'

[165:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'possible to keep my rig nice, simple, and clean. So, I\'ll delete the drivers and we\'ll look for another solution. So, we\'re going to introduce a new'

[166:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraint called transformation. And let\'s take a look at the options that it gives us. So, we can map from something to something, and on each we can use'

[166:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'location, rotation, or scale. So, that means that we can do exactly what we did with our driver, but using this constraint now. So, we\'re going to want to map from the scale of our control bone to the rotation of the constraint'

[166:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bone. So, the scale will drive the rotation. Let\'s manually set up the target. It will be the armature and the bone will be pinky.r, our control bone. We want to rotate the bone in local space,'

[166:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so let\'s switch to local space and local space. Transformation is a very powerful constraint, so let\'s take a minute to actually understand what\'s happening. So, we\'re using the scale of our target'

[166:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bone to affect the rotation of the constraint bone. For scale, we have X, Y, and Z values, and by default it is set up so the X scale will drive the X rotation, the Y scale will drive the Y'

[167:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotation, and the Z scale will drive the Z rotation. We can change the source axis here. And for example, if I set this to Z, then the Z scale will be driving the X rotation.'

[167:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, we have these options, but luckily for us, here the setup is much simpler. We want just any of the scale axis to drive the Z rotation. So, let\'s use the defaults. Z scale will drive Z rotation.'

[167:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The defaults here are set up so that initially this constraint does nothing. So, we have to set the Z minimum to zero.'

[167:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, that when scaling this bone from zero to one, the rotation of the bone will be affected. So, now what we\'re mapping is the range of scale from zero to one to a range of rotation values down here. So, when I scale this bone,'

[168:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what I want is that the finger bone curls in. Which means that it has to get a positive Z value. So, the closer scale is to zero, the'

[168:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'higher the rotation value has to be. So, I\'m going to set minimum rotation to 90. This means that a scale of zero will make the finger bone curl 90°. Let\'s test it, and it works.'

[168:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if you want this bone to curl more, you can just increase this value. So, it may be a little bit confusing that the minimum value here is a high positive value and it\'s higher than the'

[168:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'max value, but try to think of it as mapping ranges and then it makes sense. Now, if I select the middle phalange and select this one which already has the'

[169:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraint and go to constraints, copy constraints, I\'ll have my entire setup. The cool thing is that this constraint is set to mix add by default,'

[169:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so I can also manually rotate these bones, which was what I wanted. When I scale this bone down, I\'m curling the finger, but when I start scaling it'

[169:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up, nothing happens. So, if we enable the extrapolate option on the transformation constraint, then scaling up will start to affect the finger and it will start curling in the'

[169:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opposite direction, which to a degree is possible even for a realistic hand. So, let\'s keep this. So, without extrapolate, this range between 0 and 120 is all we\'ll get.'

[169:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'When we enable extrapolate, Blender takes the range that we defined and extends it into infinity in both directions. Okay, as always, we\'re taking our time'

[170:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to understand things and to try things and to learn new things. But now the whole setup is done, so let\'s just apply it to the rest of the fingers. Now, of course, I could duplicate this'

[170:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'finger again and make it bigger. That is a great option, but just to learn something new, let\'s isolate this rig. Select the pinky control, shift D and duplicate it.'

[170:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Set snapping to vertex. Snapping is off and then I\'ll move the bone with G and hold control to snap it at the next finger. Shift D again, hold control, and snap it to the next finger.'

[170:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And repeat this for the next finger and for the thumb. Now, the new control bones are not oriented with our fingers, but if I select the control and shift select the'

[170:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'base finger and press control alt and A, that will orient the control exactly as the base bone. So, let\'s do this for the rest of the fingers. Control alt A.'

[171:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Control alt A. Okay, aligning bones to each other is very important, so I wanted to show this. And this command is also found under armature transform align bones,'

[171:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'control alt and A. Now, let\'s tweak the size of these control bones. Then, I\'ll set the copy rotation'

[171:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from the control to the base finger, copy rotation, and also copy location. Let\'s do this for all fingers and the thumb. And I want the copy rotation to be local'

[171:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'space local space and mix to add. So, I\'ll hide all controls. Select all of these base fingers, change the active one to local space local space and mix to add, and then right'

[172:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'click copy to selected, right click copy to selected, right click copy to selected. Now, all bones should have the same setup. Now, setting up the transformation'

[172:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraint can be a little bit tedious for each bone, so let\'s select all bones that need to have this constraint. Then, select one of the bones on the pinky where the constraint is already'

[172:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'set up. Pose, constraints, copy constraints. And now all we have to do is change the target bone for each one. So let\'s unhide the control bones and name them properly.'

[172:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This will be ring.r, middle.r, index.r, and thumb.r. Okay, now I\'ll select both of these'

[173:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fingers, change the target to ring.r, right click, copy to selected. Then the next two, target is middle.r, right click, copy to'

[173:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'selected. Index.r, right click, copy to selected, and finally thumb.'

[173:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now if I select all control bones with individual origins and scale them'

[173:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'down, all bones should curl. And also if I rotate them on the z-axis, all bones will rotate. So I can create a quick fist.'

[173:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The fingers are set up'

[174:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and we are going to move on and automate the palm. Now let\'s quickly test the palm and you may see some weird rotation in the fingers. That is because the finger controls are not parented correctly to the respective palm bones because of the'

[174:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way I created them, but let\'s quickly parent them. Just select the finger control bone, shift select the closest bone, and parent them with keep offset. The thumb will also be parented to the'

[174:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'closest thumb bone. The function of these thumb bones may not be immediately obvious, but look at your hand and try to spread out your'

[174:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fingers and you\'ll notice that the palm also widens a bit. And that\'s because of the so-called metacarpal bones inside the palm are doing part of this motion. Also, if you make a fist and squeeze'

[175:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tightly, you\'ll notice that your pinky goes much lower than your index finger. And that is again because of movement of the metacarpal bones. Okay, it\'s just four bones, so we could manually animate'

[175:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them, but the movement of these bones is mostly automatic. What happens mostly is that the outside thumb bone moves and the other thumb bones move with it slightly. So, the inner thumb bones need to rotate'

[175:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with this outside thumb bone. What constraint could we use? Copy rotation, of course. So, select this bone, shift select the next one, and add a copy rotation constraint.'

[175:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Set local space in local space and we could set mix to add so that we can manually rotate this bone, although I don\'t think that would be necessary. But'

[175:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s have this option. Now again, select the outside bone, shift select the next thumb bone, control shift C, copy rotation, local space in local space, and mix to add.'

[176:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If I rotate the outside thumb bone, the other thumb bones rotate fully with it. That is too much. So, we can play with the influence slider and create a gradual falloff similar to what we did'

[176:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with the twist bones. So, this one will be about 0.5 and the next one about 0.25. We could also add a constraint between the two outside bones with a very, very'

[176:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'subtle influence, but I think that would be just a waste of time. What we could do though is to constrain these two bones to this outside bone as well. So, if I just select this bone, shift'

[176:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the next one, control shift C, copy rotation, local space, local space, mix to add, and reduce the influence to about 0.5. Then, rotating this outside bone will'

[176:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also affect this inside bone. And notice how the two outside bones just work together. There is absolutely no conflict between these two copy rotation constraints, and that is mainly'

[177:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because we\'re using local space. So, let\'s set up a constraint between this bone and this one, control shift C, copy rotation, local space, local space, add, and influence of about 0.25.'

[177:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if we look at this result, it looks kind of ridiculous. And that is because the movement of the'

[177:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'palm is meant to be extremely subtle. A rotation of 5° or so is already kind of extreme. So, you could add a limit rotation constraint on the outside bones so that'

[177:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you impose rotation within certain realistic limits. Feel free to do so. Personally, I won\'t do this. I want to allow the animator to do something extreme if they wanted to, and it will be up to them to keep the rotation of'

[178:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these palm bones very subtle. So, mainly we\'re going to be rotating this outside bone and occasionally the other one. And that is the full hand setup.'

[178:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Next, we are going to do the setup for the mechanical arm. For the most part, we can just symmetrize and reuse the mechanisms from the right arm. The'

[178:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanical arm is actually simpler in many ways. For example, it doesn\'t need any twist bones or palm bones. So, we can symmetrize only the parts that we need from the right arm and things will'

[178:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'be almost done. An important thing to consider here will be the slight asymmetry between the right and left arm, but I\'ll show you exactly how to handle it and we\'ll learn important'

[178:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'differences between edit mode symmetry and pose mode symmetry. Let me unhide all bones by unstarring everything and enabling the eye icon on'

[179:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all collections. I\'ll press Alt H as well and then go to edit mode and also press Alt H because bones can be visible in one mode but not in the other. And before we go on setting up'

[179:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the right arm, there are a couple of bones in this rig that need attention. Let\'s go to pose mode and try moving, rotating, and scaling the root bone. When transforming the root in any way,'

[179:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the whole character and all bones should just transform with it like a single unit. If anything behaves independently, then the root is not really fulfilling its purpose. When I move the root, the'

[179:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'arm IK doesn\'t move with it. And when I rotate it, all FK limbs are in their isolated state, so they don\'t follow the root. And also the settings bone does not move with the rig. I'

[179:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'encourage you to stop the video here and think of the reason these bones do not follow the root. Making sense of these relationships is quite important. Okay, a little hint. All of the problems I'

[180:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mentioned are a matter of simple parenting. So, if you could not figure it out the first time, maybe give it another shot with this hint in mind. Okay, here is the reason. All of these'

[180:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parts that don\'t move with the root are simply not part of its hierarchy. Let me reset everything and go to edit mode and I\'ll start only the IK collection,'

[180:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for example. And so, if you remember when I created this IK target bone, I pressed Alt P and clear parent. So, it is not parented to the root. And I did the exact same thing for the'

[180:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'FK follow bones. So, all I need to do is parent these bones to the root bone. And you should be able to do this easily, but let\'s take a look at something we haven\'t'

[181:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'explored much yet. And that is the hierarchy view. If we go to the outliner and click on this triangle to see what we have under the armature, we can then expand the armature data and'

[181:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that will give us a view of all of the bones that are directly under the armature. In other words, bones that are not parented to anything. And one of these bones is, of course, the root. If I expand its hierarchy, I can see even'

[181:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'deeper into the parenting of the bones. But we also have five other bones that are not parented to anything. And those are exactly the bones that we saw, the rig settings, the IK target bone, and'

[181:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all of the follow bones. And this hierarchy view can be very important. It can tell you a lot about the relationships between the bones in your rig. Personally, I don\'t use it'

[181:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much, and that is mainly because of the way my mind works. If I just look at this view, unless I really focus at it, it kind of looks like gibberish to me. So, it It on how your brain works. Some people will find this very useful and'

[182:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other people like me are more likely to just go to pose mode and move things around and try to figure out how the rig works. Something that Blender lacks compared to other 3D software such as Maya and Max'

[182:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a more visual hierarchy view. Hopefully, we\'ll get something like this in the near future, but for now this hierarchy view is the best we get. By the way, when I\'m in edit mode, I see the bones here under'

[182:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the armature data, but when I go to pose mode, I\'ll kind of see the same bones under pose. This still confuses me a bit, but that is what we get. So, I\'ll go back to edit mode. And now instead of'

[182:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parenting the bones in the usual way, selecting the bones, control P, keep offset, and so on, let\'s do it another way. I\'ll just select one bone that I want to parent, for example, the IK'

[182:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'target. Then go to the bone tab and you should be in edit mode. If you\'re in pose mode, this parent field will be grayed out, but in edit mode, it\'s available. Now I can click on it'

[183:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and select the root as parent, and that will set the parenting. This is what happens when you press control P. Now if you look at the hierarchy, the target bone seems to be still outside of the root hierarchy, but if I click on the'

[183:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'outliner, then it will be updated. So, it was already updated, it\'s just that the outliner view lags behind. So, now you\'ll find this bone under the root hierarchy.'

[183:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, let\'s select one of the follow bones and also parent it to the root. Let\'s select the next one. Parent it to the root and the final one and parent it to the root.'

[183:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now if I click, everything will be updated. Now for the settings bone, I can also parent it to the root, but I\'ll go back to my collections and unhide everything and instead I\'ll'

[184:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parent it to the head bone. But let\'s do it from the parent field again. I\'ll click here and type head and then click on the head bone.'

[184:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now the settings bone will be parented to the head bone. Parenting it to the root is also fine. But parenting it to the head will give me a more stable location for this bone. It will always be near the head.'

[184:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, great. Now everything should be fixed and the character in the whole rig should move, rotate and scale with the root bone. By the way, I admit that these issues that we just fixed were an'

[184:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'oversight on my part. I could have planned the videos perfectly and just told you to click here and then click there and parent those bones. But real rigging is different from following a'

[184:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tutorial. It\'s a lot messier. You often make a mistake, then you have to go back and fix it. So the way I create this course, I have a perfect idea of the rig we are building and the major steps that'

[185:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we need to take. At the same time, I don\'t have every little step written down while recording the videos. So this gives the videos a good structure, but we also get ourselves in more real-world'

[185:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'situations where we have to go back and fix something. You are almost out of the sack when it comes to your understanding of the rigging tools in Blender. But'

[185:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there is another important aspect that is not part of Blender at all and that is your mindset. If you believe that everything has to be smooth sailing from start to finish, it can cause you to'

[185:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'give up and fail. Accepting that you will have to bang your head against the wall occasionally is better for your long-term success. Rigging is both artistic and technical, and getting'

[185:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frustrated occasionally is normal. Okay, back to actual rigging. Let\'s set up the mechanical arm now. As I said in the beginning, about 80% of the work will be done for us by just symmetrizing the'

[186:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right arm mechanism. And the rest will be restoring the drivers, which are not symmetrized, and most importantly, tweaking the symmetry. Okay, so let\'s hide that we don\'t need.'

[186:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m going to hide everything except for'

[186:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the main base bones. And now I want to isolate these twist bones on a separate layer, because I don\'t want to symmetrize them, and I want to have a nice way to just hide'

[186:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'them away. So, let\'s hide these big bones, which will give me access to all of the twist bones. I\'ll select them all, press M, new collection, and call it twists. And let\'s do the same for the legs.'

[187:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hide the big bones, select all of the twist bones, M, and move them to the twists collection. And now I can hide the twists. I\'ll press alt H,'

[187:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and now unhide FK and IK bones, and the hand bones. Now I can select everything here on the right arm.'

[187:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s just box select over everything, and now I want to deselect the palm bones, because I don\'t want to symmetrize them. I\'m holding control while box selecting,'

[187:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and that deselects the bones. Okay, actually I want to go to edit mode and delete the arm bones that we already have on the left side.'

[188:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Make sure that X symmetry is disabled here to avoid deleting any bones on the other side and then press X and delete. Now again, select everything on the right'

[188:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'side including the IK pole target and so on. And then control and box select only the palm bones.'

[188:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, this looks good. Let\'s right click and symmetrize. I\'ll go to pose mode.'

[188:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Grab the IK target and move it a bit. And then the FK and move it as well. So, I can see that the fingers weren\'t properly parented to the hand.'

[188:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That is because we didn\'t symmetrize the palm bones and so part of the hierarchy and the parenting was lost. But that\'s okay. Let\'s just start the main bones. Go to edit mode.'

[189:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I also have to start the hand bones because the fingers are on that layer. So now what I need to do is parent all of the first phalanges and the control bones'

[189:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the hand bone. Control P keep offset. Now the fingers will move with the arm. Okay, now let\'s go to our settings bone'

[189:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and create properties for the IK FK switching of this arm and also for the follow mechanism. So, we\'ll go to the bone tab. Scroll down.'

[189:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Click on new twice. And then edit the property. Let\'s call this one left arm FK IK'

[189:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Set step to one and press okay. And the other property will be left arm follow. Step to one and press okay. Okay, first I\'m going to right click on'

[190:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the left arm FK IK property. Copy data path. And to set up the IK FK switching, I have to focus on the main bones. So,'

[190:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll start them. Select the upper arm. Go to constraints. Right click on the influence of copy transforms IK. Add a driver.'

[190:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Expression to var. Single property. Select the armature and paste what we copied into the path. And right click on the influence. Copy the driver.'

[190:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to the lower arm. Paste the driver. And paste it on the hand as well. Now, we can switch between IK and FK for the mechanical arm.'

[190:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, let\'s start only the FK bones. Actually, before that I want to switch IK FK to zero so that I\'m in FK mode and I can test the'

[191:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanism. And also, let\'s right click on the left arm follow property and copy the data path. Go to the follow FK bone. Go to constraints.'

[191:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Right click on the copy rotation influence. Add a driver. Expression var. Single property. Armature and paste.'

[191:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if I rotate the spine a bit, I will be able to test the follow mechanism, and it works. Perfect so far. Now, we just need to'

[191:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tweak the positions of these arm and hand and finger bones because the right organic arm and the left mechanical arm are slightly different. They are slightly asymmetrical.'

[192:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, let\'s go to edit mode and start aligning. There is not a huge amount of work that we need to do, just slight tweaks on each joint, but we have to be careful'

[192:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and precise because there are overlapping bones that need to stay aligned. Before you begin, make sure that X symmetry is disabled because we want these two arms to have slight'

[192:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'asymmetry. So, I\'ll remove all stars, and I\'ll have the eye icon on the main bones, FK bones, IK bones, and the hand. Then, I\'ll carefully select all bones'

[192:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the arm and hand and press shift H. The fingers will need the most tweaking, so let\'s quickly align the arm first,'

[192:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then we\'ll come to the fingers. So, I\'ll hide the hand collection for now. Okay, looking at the arm, it looks well aligned, but I imagine that this'

[193:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanical arm has a ball socket joint similar to the organic one right in this area. So, to tweak that, I\'ll select the whole upper arm,'

[193:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and that includes the IK pole target as well. And I\'ll shift click on one of the big bones, and again select everything. Now, this big bone is active, and its pivot point is here. So, if I switch to'

[193:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'active element and press S to scale, I\'m scaling from this point and I\'m scaling the whole set of bones as one unit, so nothing will get misaligned. So, I\'ll move and rotate this part'

[193:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'slightly to align it with this ball socket joint that I imagine. Next, I\'ll focus on the wrist. So, here we have this soft part of the arm and that is where it is supposed to'

[194:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bend, in my opinion. So, I\'ll move these bones at that position. And then, I\'ll make again one of these bones active, select all of the rest and now if I press S, I\'ll be scaling from this'

[194:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'point. And I\'ll make these bones slightly smaller. Other than that, it\'s looking good. So, let\'s focus on this elbow joint now.'

[194:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll select two of these big bones. And then, I want to look at these bones exactly from the top. Meaning that this upper part of the bones should be'

[194:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aligned perfectly with my view. And Blender has a function to do just that. If we go to view, align view, align view to active, we can choose from a couple of options. They\'re not very intuitive, so I\'ll right click on this option and'

[194:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'add it to my quick favorites. Now, I can just press Q and go through these one by one. So, this is a perfect front view, a perfect back view,'

[195:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these are side views, and here we have bottom view and the last one will be my top view, which I was looking for. So, here I see this part of the'

[195:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanical arm and I imagine that here would be the point where the lower arm rotates on. So, I\'ll select this joint and move it into place.'

[195:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I guess this joint needs to move a little bit deeper into the volume of the arm, something like this. So, I\'ll box select like this to also include the mechanism bones'

[195:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and move this point. Maybe slight adjustment of the hand as well. And this is looking good.'

[195:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I\'ll go to the normal front view and then back to perspective. There\'s a chance that these small mechanism bones lost their alignment to the big bone. So, if I just select them like this'

[196:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I\'ll make sure that one of the big bones has the bright yellow outline, which means that it\'s active and I\'ll try to remember the shortcut for aligning bones. It is control alt and A.'

[196:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if I undo and then redo you will notice this very slight movement of the smaller bones. So, they were just slightly misaligned, but now I fixed it.'

[196:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, and the last thing that I\'m going to do is isolate what I have here. There is a chance that the pole target got slightly misaligned, very slightly, but still we want to fix it.'

[196:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, with vertex snapping, I\'m going to move the bone, hold control and snap it at the elbow and then press G Y and offset it again. Okay, now I can go out of local mode'

[197:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and unhide the hand collection. And now I\'ll hide the big control bones and just focus on aligning the actual fingers. And then we\'ll align the'

[197:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'controls just like we did earlier for the left hand. For the alignment of the fingers is always I like to use volume snapping. So, let\'s just grab these joints one by'

[197:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. And I\'ll snap them where the details of the model indicate that the bending will occur. Let\'s roll these finger bones'

[197:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so that they align with the geometry exactly. Then I\'ll do my straightening technique. I\'ll switch pivot point to bounding box'

[198:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'center, orientation to normal, enable scaling, and scale on the Z axis, press zero and then enter. Then from the side view, it seems like'

[198:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the base of the fingers weren\'t snapped exactly in the center of the volume here. So, try this. Enable snap PO object. This is a special object for volume snapping, which considers several'

[198:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'overlapping objects. Here the fingers and the palm are not connected. They\'re separate geometries. And so, when we enable this option, we\'ll get better volume snapping. There'

[198:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we go. So, after this, if you need to tweak the roll and straighten the fingers again, let\'s do the slight bending technique as'

[199:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well. Again, using normal mode, I\'ll move the middle phalanges slightly on the X axis, and that will give all fingers a slight bend. Let\'s align the thumb now in the same'

[199:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way. Snap the bones where you see the bending details. Tweak the roll.'

[199:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And straighten the bones. Create the bend. Now, if I go to pose mode, the bones will move slightly. That is because we'

[199:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'haven\'t aligned the big control bones yet, and so the fingers jump to their position because of copy location. Let\'s go to edit mode. Alt H to unhide the bones.'

[199:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go into local mode. And then, with vertex snapping, let\'s snap each control to its respective finger. And then, select the control, shift'

[200:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the first phalange, and press control alt A to align the controls to the fingers. Go out of local mode. Now, I can go into pose mode.'

[200:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Switch to individual origins and select all controls. And if I scale them down, I should see all fingers bend in their natural direction. In edit mode, I\'ll tweak the roll of the'

[200:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thumb just slightly because this looks more natural to me. Okay, perfect. Let\'s select all bones. Alt R, Alt G, Alt S.'

[200:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, the alignment of the mechanical arm should be perfect. And in the beginning, I mentioned that the X symmetry for pose mode and edit mode are different. Here is what I mean.'

[200:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If I go to edit mode and enable X symmetry, and move the left shoulder, for example, the right shoulder will move exactly with it. If I disable X symmetry here and tweak only the left shoulder a bit,'

[201:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then enable symmetry again, you see that as soon as I press G or R or S, the other side synchronizes with it. It gives me perfect symmetry of'

[201:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these bones. And often that is what we want. But for example, with our left and right arm, that is not what we want. We want the arms to keep a slight asymmetry of their origin points. So, this point'

[201:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is slightly different from this one and this one to this one and so on. So, if you need to tweak one of the arms in edit mode, don\'t forget to disable X symmetry because if you have it enabled,'

[201:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that will symmetrize the bones and we don\'t want that. On the other hand, if you want to tweak the legs, then do enable X symmetry. So, I want to disable X symmetry just to be safe, but before I'

[202:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do, let\'s go to pose mode. And notice that X symmetry is off now, even though it was on in edit mode. X symmetry in edit mode and pose mode are actually different. If I enable X'

[202:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'symmetry for pose mode and move the left leg IK for example, the right leg will also move and vice versa. And that makes sense because these two legs were perfectly'

[202:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'symmetrical. But let\'s try this with the arms. I\'ll start the FK collection, select the upper arm and rotate it. And notice that the left arm rotates as'

[202:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well, even though these bones are slightly asymmetrical. So, X symmetry in pose mode is just based on the bones names. As long as you have two bones with the same name and'

[202:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this option enabled, then the bones with the same name will transform simultaneously. It\'s a bit like having a special copy transforms constraint between the two.'

[203:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay? And it doesn\'t matter how asymmetrical these bones are in edit mode. So, for example, I can go to edit mode, deselect the X symmetry, and make a big change to this arm. Then back to pose'

[203:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mode, as long as I have this option enabled, X symmetry will work for these two bones. So, let me undo because this was just for demonstration. Okay, that was all I wanted to show for'

[203:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this chapter. We created the mechanisms for the left arm. We aligned them properly with slight asymmetry to the right arm, but at the same time we kept the symmetrical names of these bones, and that will allow us to symmetrize the'

[203:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'poses of both arms in pose mode. And that can be useful in animation. Our rig has progressed nicely, and it\'s getting quite complex. So, the next step will be to organize these bones on'

[203:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collections, and we\'ll also take a very special step that will make our rig easier to understand, easier to weight paint, and also easier to export to game engines and such. More about that in the'

[204:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'next video. In this video, we\'ll improve the organization of the rig, which includes creating bone collections and shapes. But first, we\'re going to apply a'

[204:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'special technique. We\'ll separate the deforming bones completely from the rest of mechanism and control bones. If you remember in level one and two, we had some bones that were deforming, but also'

[204:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'acted as controls or mechanisms. And that may have been confusing at times, but it was okay because our rigs were still quite simple. But this rig is approaching professional quality and'

[204:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'complexity, so we have to take organization even more seriously. Implementing this will take a little bit of time and effort, so it\'s important to understand that the benefits of this technique are great. It improves the'

[205:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'organization of your rig by a lot. It makes weight painting a lot easier and as a bonus, it will make your character easier to export to game engines and other 3D applications. I hope you see'

[205:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the positives, so let\'s do it. This process should be initiated when you\'re fairly certain that you\'re not going to be changing your deform bones anymore. You\'re not going to change their'

[205:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'positions, you\'re not going to tweak the number of twist bones, for example, and so on and so forth. The rig should be in stable state. And the first step in the process will be to identify the bones in our current rig that should act as'

[205:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'deforming bones. So, let\'s unhide all collections and press Alt H and in edit mode, I\'ll also press Alt H because I want to be sure that all bones are visible and then'

[205:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll go back to pose mode. Now, let\'s see what is definitely not deforming bones. My torso control collection contains only controls. So, they\'re not deforming. So, I can hide this'

[206:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'collection. The MCH collection currently only contains these MCH bones for the foot. They are also not deforming, so let\'s hide them.'

[206:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The IK and FK collections contain only control and mechanism bones for the IK and FK setups. So, they\'re definitely not deforming. Let\'s hide them. So, now I have all of my deforming'

[206:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones, but also some non-deforming ones. So, let\'s start going through the rig and identifying our actual deform bones. The head, neck, chest, shoulder, and the next chest and'

[206:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spine bones will all be deforming. So, select them, press M, create a new collection and let\'s call it DEF for deforming.'

[206:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I\'m going to hide this collection so that I can focus on the remaining bones. On the arm, the actual deforming bones are the twist bones.'

[207:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the big bone is a mechanism bone. So, let\'s select these big bones and press H to hide them. Okay, next I\'m going to select all of'

[207:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these twist bones and the hand and also the palm bones. All of them should be deforming, so I\'ll move them to the DEF collection.'

[207:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'For the fingers, I want the actual phalanges to be deforming, but these big control bones will be non-deforming, so select them, hide them, then box select the fingers, M,'

[207:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
