[245:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the control bones. Our rig will look nice and become user-friendly. And once the shapes are in place, I think you\'ll also really appreciate the split between controls and deform bones that we worked'

[246:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on. Bone shapes are not just a nice visual touch. They are essential for making the rig more readable and easy to understand. You already learned about 90% of bone shape techniques in level'

[246:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two, but there is one important new technique called override transforms. You\'ll also learn how the orientation of your shape objects is related to the orientation of the bones themselves,'

[246:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which can save you a lot of time and clicks. So, stay tuned for that. And to save time, I\'m going to provide bone shapes for you. In your downloads, you\'ll find a file called wgts.blend. Let\'s go to object mode, and we can'

[246:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'append the content of that file by going to file, append. Find the wgts file, double-click it, go to collection,'

[246:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the wgts collection, and press append. And that added the skull collection with a variety of shapes into our rig file. For the most part, these are the same'

[247:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shapes we used in level two with a couple of new additions. If you want to use your own shapes, that\'s all right, too. But, I\'ll be using these ones. And let\'s start working on the shapes.'

[247:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Select the rig and go to pose mode. And many bones in this rig are going to get this circle shape.'

[247:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I\'ll try to isolate the bones that need this circle widget. I\'ll hide the IK bones. Because I want to give most of the FK'

[247:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones, most of the spine bones, and the finger bones, the circular widget. So, I\'ll select the main finger controls, the main torso controls,'

[248:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and hide them. I\'ll also hide the root and the settings bone. And I want all of these bones to have the circular widget. So, just select one of them,'

[248:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then press A to select the rest, go to the bone tab, and I\'ll contract everything and expand viewport display. And for custom object, I\'ll look for circle.'

[248:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then right click and copy to selected. And that will set the circular widget for all of these bones. Actually, I didn\'t want to set it for the shoulders. So, let\'s unassign the shape and hide the bones.'

[248:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, all I need to do is tweak the size and position of these circles, and I\'ll have a big portion of the rig set up. But before that, here is a tip that I'

[248:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'think is very important. Notice that all circles were oriented exactly as I want them. I will not need to rotate them much. I\'ll only need to scale and move them. And here is why. I\'ll go to object mode,'

[249:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the circular widget, and under and panel tool enable origins. And pay attention to the Y axis. As you'

[249:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'probably know by now, the length of a bone is always aligned with its Y axis. And the axis of the bone shapes aligns with the bones, which means that when this circle is applied as a bone shape,'

[249:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it will be aligned to the bone like this. This will be the head of the bone. And this will be the rest of the bone. So, when creating bone shapes, always'

[249:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'pay attention to the Y axis. If you need to tweak it, you can enable origins in object mode. And then using the rotation gizmo will actually rotate the origin. So, you can'

[249:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'align the Y axis any way you like. Once you\'re done, don\'t forget to disable origins. Okay, that is why all of our circles are'

[250:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'aligned almost perfectly now. So, next I\'m going to go into a little time lapse. All I\'m doing is selecting shapes that should have similar size and then I\'m tweaking their scale.'

[250:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Personally, I hold Alt and Shift which tweaks all shapes at once. If that doesn\'t work for you, just tweak one shape. Then right click and copy all to selected.'

[250:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Okay, this is what I\'m getting for now.'

[251:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Some important notes. Here I have the palm bones and I\'m going to want a different shape for them. So, I\'ll select all of them. Remove the shape of one, right click, copy to selected.'

[251:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here these two shapes are overlapping. I\'ll move this one slightly up and this one slightly down so that I know which one is controlling which direction.'

[251:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And next, I\'m going to go to the armature tab, display, and disable in front. Because my goal for these shapes is that'

[251:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they\'re easily visible without any transparency. Now I can enable transparency temporarily in pose mode by clicking on the X-ray button. And I\'m going to do it with my pie menu.'

[252:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, I can quickly make the bones transparent so that I can see these bones for example, which don\'t have shapes yet. And I can also turn off transparency to check the final state of my shapes.'

