[319:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looks good. And keep in mind that the shoulder does not have an incredible range of motion. You can raise the shoulders to about this height and you can move them forward to about this much. Probably around 20°'

[320:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in each direction. Okay, the organic part of the body is starting to look really good. You could certainly spend more time on the very'

[320:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'difficult areas such as the hips and the neck area. The more time you spend, the better results you\'ll get. We got it to a really good state, almost perfect considering that we are just relying on'

[320:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'weights and not so much on automated bones. You can probably squeeze another 10% of quality if you keep painting for another hour or two, but since it is just a repetition of the same process'

[320:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'over and over, I\'ll skip that and move on to the mechanical arm. In this video, we\'ll weight paint the mechanical arm of the character. So, you\'ll add even more weight painting'

[321:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tools and workflows to your skill set. Now, let\'s disable wireframe. I\'ll also hide these widgets. And let\'s see how we can handle the'

[321:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanical arm. First of all, if we try to parent the mechanical arm to the rig with automatic weights, as we saw earlier, it doesn\'t work and it doesn\'t work because of this error'

[321:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that we are getting. If I click on it, I can expand this window and you\'ll see bone heat waiting failed to find solution for one or more bone. I mentioned this problem all the way back in level one because it is fairly'

[321:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'common. As your characters get more and more complex, you\'ll definitely see it. This simply means that the automatic weights algorithm failed. It didn\'t work, so you will not get any weights. I'

[321:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have a specialized video about this problem and now you\'re definitely advanced enough, you can watch it and find out all solutions to this problem. But the solution we\'ll apply in this'

[322:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video will be to simply set the weights manually. The bones for the mechanical arms are relatively simple. We just have the upper arm, lower arm, hand, and finger'

[322:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones. So, I\'ll go to the mechanical arm and I\'ll try to split it into parts because most of it is a hard surface object and it doesn\'t need to bend. So, we\'ll split'

[322:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it into parts and just assign each part to a specific bone. Let\'s go to edit mode. And I\'ll place my mouse over parts of the upper arm and just press L.'

[322:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll also select this pipe here. It might be easier to select in polygon mode. This is my upper arm. I\'ll press P and'

[322:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'separate it into a separate object. Now, this part here will be slightly'

[323:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'special. It will be semi-soft and it will bend in this area. So, let\'s press P and separate it into a new object. And we\'ll handle it separately. And similarly, this cable here I\'ll'

[323:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'split into a separate object and I\'ll see how I\'m going to handle it. Now, I\'ll select these parts here for the lower arm. And this part, but not this one.'

[323:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I\'ll split these into a separate object. And this will be another soft part. So, I\'ll split it as a separate object.'

[323:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Next, we have the palm. It\'s a single object, so I\'ll just select it and separate it. And I\'ll keep all fingers as their own object for now.'

[324:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The deforming bone for the upper arm is called def.upperarm.l. So, let\'s copy this name.'

[324:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to the upper arm geometry, edit mode, select everything, go into data, vertex groups, expand the search field,'

[324:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and paste the name here. Select it and press assign. Now, the upper arm will be controlled by this bone. Let\'s do the same for the lower arm.'

[324:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Just select all vertices, find lowerarm.l, and assign. Now, this part will be assigned to def.'

[324:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hand.l and press assign. So, now we have a big portion of the'

[325:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mechanical arm moving. Now, let\'s see what we can do about this soft part. I\'ll select the rig, shift select the soft part, and go to weight'

[325:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'paint mode. I\'ll alt click on the lower arm bone and shift alt and click on the upper arm. And then, I\'ll go to weights, assign automatic from bones.'

[325:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is basically the same algorithm as automatic weights, but it will only be applied for the selected bones here. Now, this seems to kind of work, but the'

[325:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lower arm has too much influence over the soft part. So let\'s select the upper arm bone and paint positive weights here. And at the same time, I want to remove weights from'

[326:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the lower part of this soft transition. It\'s starting to work. Maybe it will need a little bit of softening here. Just distribute the weights'

[326:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'until it looks good. Now I can rotate this mechanical arm in all sorts of direction, which doesn\'t make sense.'

[326:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It should only be able to rotate on a single axis. So in pose mode, select this lower arm control bone for the FK, go to item, switch rotation mode to XYZ Euler,'

[326:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and test which axis the arm should rotate on. For me, it\'s the X axis, so I\'ll lock Y and Z. Now this rotation works quite well.'

[327:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We have a little problem here with this mechanical part. We\'ll fix it with additional rigging. And the soft transition is also behaving nicely.'

[327:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now for this soft transition, I can just go to edit mode,'

[327:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select this outer loop, press control plus to select about half of this part, find DEF lower arm.l, and assign it to it,'

[327:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because this part of the soft transition will be affected by this bone here. Click assign. Then press control I. Find d e f hand.l.'

[327:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Select it and assign. Now, I really like this effect. We have this slight pinching because'

[328:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there is no smooth transition between the weights, but that kind of works to our advantage. It kind of makes it look like there is something hard underneath this soft material. However, if you want to soften it a bit,'

[328:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the rig, shift select the soft part, go to weight paint mode, select these two bones that affect the weights of this part, go to weights, smooth,'

[328:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and choose selected pose bones. This will smooth the weights between the selected bones. You can increase or decrease the iterations. I\'ll just keep it to one.'

[328:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now we have slightly smoother weights and I kind of like this. So, I\'ll keep it like this. Now, let\'s go to the fingers.'

[329:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Select the rig, shift select the fingers, go to weight paint mode. And now we can use the assign automatic from bones technique. What I could do is select these three fingers,'

[329:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'go to vertex selection, press L over this finger to select the vertices, and then assign automatic from bones. And that will assign weights only for'

[329:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the selected bones and only to the selected vertices. Let\'s repeat this for the remaining fingers. &gt;&gt; And now let\'s test.'

[329:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The weights can be improved and made a little bit harder. Here the topology of these fingers itself will not allow us to achieve perfect deformations,'

[330:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but we can get pretty close. And in fact, I think this is looking okay already. Now, the bigger problem here is that my point of rotation of the base of the finger is a bit off.'

[330:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, unfortunately, I\'ll have to go to edit mode. I\'ll switch to solid shading and double X-ray. And I\'ll select the base of the finger'

[330:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and offset it a bit. Like this. As you do this, try to keep the fingers as straight as possible. And let\'s do this for the remaining'

[330:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fingers. And I would recommend selecting all finger bones and pressing shift H to avoid selecting and moving any unrelated bones. Okay, if I rotate all fingers on their'

[331:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'local Z axis, I\'m now getting something much better. Now, I don\'t exactly like how these'

[331:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fingers bunch together. This is because of the roll of the bones, so let\'s try to fix it. I\'ll go to solid shading and enable'

[331:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'x-ray and just select all bones of this finger for example. And then press control R and roll them slightly. And same here.'

[331:49] [scene:talk]
