[369:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then shift select elbow.l and press control shift C copy rotation. Go to constraints. Set them to local space and local space. And start MCH other.'

[369:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the automation already works. It\'s just too strong. So, let\'s go to the constraints and reduce the influence. Influence of about 0.2 or even slightly'

[370:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'below that is perfect. We can disable Y and Z here because they don\'t do anything. Depending on the role of your bone, you may have to invert the X axis.'

[370:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That is not the case for me, so I\'ll keep it disabled. If I switch mix to add, I can even keep manual control over this bone. So, that\'s it. That\'s the copy rotation'

[370:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'solution. Let\'s reset the rig and delete the constraint because I want to explore the last one, and that is the transformation'

[370:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constraint. Let\'s start MCH other again. Select the lower arm bone, shift select the elbow bone, control shift C'

[370:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'transformation. Go to constraints. We want to use local space and local space. We want to map from rotation to rotation.'

[371:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And because I carefully created this elbow bone, it has very similar orientations to the lower arm bone. And therefore, we can simply map X rotation to X rotation. And that is also'

[371:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'why the copy rotation solution worked so effortlessly. Now, to create a relationship between the driver, which is the lower arm, and the driven, which is the elbow,'

[371:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I have to map from X 0 to, let\'s say, 100. And then two, minimum zero again, and maximum around 20. If you remember in In copy rotation constraint, we set'

[371:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'influence to about 0.2 and by mapping 100 to 20, we achieve the same result. And there it is.'

[372:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Awesome. We\'ll keep going deeper into mechanical rigging and you will learn a constraint that is so easy to use and at the same time so powerful that using it feels a'

[372:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bit like cheating. It allows us to create complex automations like this with multiple parts moving with complete precision. This magic is based on the action constraint. Action is Blender\'s'

[372:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'word for animation and so this constraint makes the transform or the movement of one bone play an animation on other bones. For example here, moving this control up'

[372:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'triggers this animation on these other four bones. And moving it in the opposite direction plays the animation in reverse. And I have also linked the scaling of'

[372:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this control to an animation of the fingers so that scaling this control down will create a fist pose. Let\'s learn how to do this. It\'s really not difficult. First, let\'s see how the'

[373:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'action constraint works in principle. In a new blend scene, I\'m going to create an armature, go to edit mode, and make a couple of copies of the default bone.'

[373:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This bone will be the control for the action constraint. So let\'s name it control. The names of the other bones are not that important,'

[373:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but it is important to create an animation for them. I can keyframe these bones at one by pressing I. And then I\'ll go to frame 10.'

[373:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I\'ll just give a random animation to each of these bones. I\'ll move, rotate, and scale each one. Now select all bones and press I to'

[374:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keyframe the animation. And now we have something like this, completely random and freestyle. Before we set up the constraint, it\'s important to understand Blender\'s action editor. Let\'s switch this window to dope'

[374:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sheet. Dope sheet is one of the animation editors, and it has a sub mode called action editor. In here, I can see the currently active animation for this armature and its'

[374:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'name, so I can rename it here. And I\'ll name it AC_ AC stands for action constraint, and in this case, I\'ll just give it a random'

[374:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'name like anim. If you\'re using Blender 4.4 and later, you\'re going to see the new slotted actions here. They are a new way to organize our animations. So the action acts as a container for sub actions, and'

[374:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the sub action is what actually contains the keyframes. So in this case, I\'ll simply name the action something like action constraints. And the actual action, I\'ll name anim.'

[375:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the cool thing about this new system is that if you have additional action constraints, you can place them all under the action constraints top action. So it\'s a nice way to organize your'

[375:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scene. Now the action is almost set up, but if we switch to graph editor and zoom in on the curves,'

[375:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as we discussed in level one, by default, Blender creates ease in and ease out between the key frames. Which means that the action starts slow,'

[375:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then speeds up, and then at the end it slows down again. To avoid this, select all bones. In the graph editor, select all key frames. Press T and choose linear.'

[376:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now the animation of this bone will move linearly. And this is important for the action constraint because the movement of the control will be linear. So we'

[376:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t want the animation to have ease in and ease out. If I go back to the action editor, I can also select the key frames here and'

[376:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'press T and choose my interpolation. Now the action is set up. I\'m also going to enable the shield to make sure I don\'t lose this action. Then go to one of the animated bones.'

[376:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to constraints and set up an action constraint. The target will be the armature and the bone will be our control bone. So the control bone will trigger the'

[376:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'animation. On the target, we can define what exactly will trigger that animation. Here I\'m going to go for Y location in local space. The local Y axis of a bone is the one'

[377:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that runs along its length. Then under action, we have to specify which action will be played. It will be our AC anim, of course. In Blender 4.4 at this point, you\'ll'

[377:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have to select your top action and that will give you access to a slot, which in this case is automatically set to anim because it\'s the only one. But if you had more than one sub action, you\'ll have to select it from here.'

[377:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Other than that, you can keep following the tutorial. So please keep this in mind for the actual practice session, which will start shortly. And then we have to define the start and end of the animation. So, I\'ll set it'

[377:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from 1 to 10, which is our full animation. But, just keep in mind that if you set this to 5, then you can tell the constraint that you only want to play half of the animation. And finally, we have to specify the'

[377:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'range of values that will trigger this animation. Min will, of course, be zero because that is the default position of the bone before it is moved. And for max, I\'m going to try one.'

[378:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, moving this bone up will play the animation for the constrained bone. If you want the animation to be'

[378:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
