[396:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'would be a better practice, but here I want to show you how you can reuse the same action and trigger different parts of this action using different transforms of the same control. So,'

[396:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s just keep AC secret as it is, select all finger controls, press I to key frame them, go to frame 10, Switch orientation to local and individual origins. Press R, Z and'

[396:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rotate the fingers down. S to scale and bend. Then grab the thumb control and adjust it.'

[397:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Something like this. Select all controls'

[397:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I to keyframe them. Then select the keyframes, T linear. Okay, now I\'ll select this control.'

[397:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Shift select one of the finger controls. Control shift C action. Go to constraints. The target will be one of the scale axis. It really doesn\'t matter which one. And world space and local space'

[397:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will not make much of a difference. Range min will be from one to zero because the default scale is one and we want to scale the control down to'

[397:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'trigger the fist animation. So actually, max will be not zero, but something like 0.5 because I don\'t want to scale this bone all the way to nothingness to trigger the entire animation. 0.5 will be nice.'

[398:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then we\'ll set action to AC secret and start to one and end to the 10. Now select the remaining finger'

[398:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'controls. Shift select this one. Pose, constraints, copy constraints. And our fist automation is done. As I said earlier, action constraint'

[398:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'does not prevent you from manually animating these controls that have the constraint. Okay, so the scale part of this control'

[398:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is a little bit illogical. If you wanted something like this, you would probably add another control in the hand area and use it as a trigger for the fist animation. My main goal here was to show you'

[398:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'different workflows that are possible with this constraint. That is why I reused the same action and the same control. The idea was to show how one control can trigger different parts of the same action on exactly the bones we'

[399:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'choose. Hopefully, that gives you a better understanding of this amazing action constraint that you can apply for yourself. And that will be all for this chapter, and it also concludes the mechanical rigging part of level three.'

[399:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I hope it was a good introduction to mechanical rigging. Again, I want to stress the importance of fundamentals, which are the same for mechanical rigging, human rigging, horse rigging, and so on.'

[399:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Your understanding of major rigging techniques like armatures, bones, mechanisms, and weight painting is now quite solid. This last section of'

[399:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rigging isn\'t scary is dedicated to another key tool, shape keys. If you come from another software, you may already know shape keys as morph targets or blend shapes. We\'ll use shape keys to improve difficult deformations in our'

[400:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rig as well as for creating a new type of a face rig. So, let\'s dive in. To explain the basics of shape keys, I\'ll be using a simpler object like Suzanne. And then we\'ll go back to our character'

[400:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'model and apply what we learned in practice. So, shape keys are a predefined deformation of your mesh. To create a shape key, we have to go to the data tab, shape keys, and click on the plus button. The first shape key is'

[400:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'always called basis, and it represents the default state of the mesh. Shape keys are vertex offsets from this basis. So, this default shape is essential. Therefore, as a best practice, you'

[400:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'should start working on shape keys when your character is finished. Similar to weight painting, Blender is quite forgiving in this regard, and you may be able to do some changes to your mesh even after you started working on shape'

[400:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keys. But, you may run into problems such as your shape keys looking weird or not working at all. So, the best practice is finalize the modeling, rigging, and even weight painting, and then do the shape keys. To create our'

[401:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first actual shape key, I\'ll click the plus button here again. And that gives us key one. I can rename this key by double-clicking on it, and here I\'m going to stretch the ear, so I\'ll name it ear stretch.'

[401:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, if I go to edit mode, I can select vertices that I want to tweak for this shape key and start moving them around. Using proportional editing can help you achieve more organic deformations.'

[401:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I can control the falloff by scrolling the mouse wheel here. And I\'ll stretch this ear on the X axis. Now, if I go back to object mode, the monkey will be back to its basis shape. That is because value here is set to zero, but'

[401:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'if I set it to one, it will assume the shape of my shape key. The next shape I\'m going to create is designed to teach you some of the main properties of shape keys, namely that shape keys can be'

[401:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'combined. When they are combined, they are actually added on top of each other. And finally, that the offset of the vertices that a shape key produces is linear. Let\'s see what that means. I\'ll set my ear stretch to zero and'

[402:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create a new shape key. And let\'s call it ear rotate because I\'ll try to rotate this ear. Now, I\'ll go to edit mode again, and I have the vertices selected and proportional editing. So, now I\'ll'

[402:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'set the 3D cursor around here and set the pivot point to 3D cursor. And then I\'ll try to rotate the ear up like this. So now in object mode, if I increase the'

[402:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'value of this new shape key, it may kind of look like it\'s rotating, but really, if we take the position of this vertex and move a bit and record it again,'

[402:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll see that this vertex moves in a straight line. So for shape keys, it doesn\'t matter how you edit your vertices. Once the shape key is established, the vertices will just move linearly from the basis towards the final shape. Now let\'s cover the mixing'

[403:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of shape keys. We have this ear moving up and then stretching horizontally. So stretching brings it up to here, and the other shape keys moves it up to here. So when'

[403:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we blend these together, you may expect that you\'ll get the average of the two shape keys, but that is not what happens. What happens is that both shape keys are added together. In other words, the linear offset of both shape keys are'

[403:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'added together. And this is very important. This is what will enable us to create the face rig later on, and it will be possible to, for example, open the mouth and create a smile at the same time. And the linear nature of shape'

[403:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keys allows us to do cool stuff like going beyond the initial shape key we established. So for example, for the stretch key, I\'ll need to select it and then I can set max to two. And now I\'ll be able to stretch this ear'

[403:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'even further. This just means that the vertices keep moving along their linear path. We can also set negative values. Let\'s go to the other shape key, and I\'ll set range min to minus one.'

[404:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now I can set the value to minus one, which will bring the vertices in the opposite direction. So if the direction of the vertex is like this, they can simply move in the'

[404:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opposite direction like this. Next I\'ll cover a couple of tools and scenarios that can be confusing while working with shape keys. Okay, let\'s set this to zero and let\'s select the ear'

[404:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stretch and until now we edited these vertices in edit mode and as soon as I switch to edit mode the mesh will assume the shape of the selected shape key. So, if I select another one, the mesh'

[404:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will switch to this shape. Now, shape keys are very organic so you may wish to sculpt them, but if you switch to sculpt mode with this ear stretch selected and set to zero, first you\'ll see the basis shape and if you'

[405:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'try to sculpt, absolutely nothing will happen. That is because value needs to be set to one in order to sculpt this shape. Now, I can use my sculpt tools to edit this shape.'

[405:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, now in sculpt mode I can also activate another shape key and keep sculpting. It\'s important to understand that what you\'re editing is the selected shape key only. Having another shape active which'

[405:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is mixing with the one you\'re editing may not be what you want. So, you may want to set this to zero. But in other cases, you may actually want to see how these two shapes will mix together and then having both shapes active can be'

[405:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'useful. In edit mode, you will only see the active shape unless you select another shape that you want to mix and click on this button. Now, I can go'

[405:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to the stretch key and edit it in edit mode and see how it will mix with another shape. Okay, I\'m not sure if we\'ll use these techniques exactly, but I want to give them to you because they can be useful'

[406:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and they can cause confusion and I believe this will be more than enough to start applying shape keys in practice. I\'ll just quickly create a new shape key. Set value to one.'

[406:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Go to sculpt mode. and let\'s name it smile. And shape the mouth of Suzanne is a smile. And I think you will begin to see how we'

[406:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can use shape keys for facial animation. But before that, we\'ll cover another common use of shape keys, and that is improving the deformations of difficult areas like elbows, knees, and even shoulders.'

[406:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now that we understand shape keys well, let\'s put them into practice on our character to improve the deformations of elbow, knees, and to some extent the shoulder.'

[406:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This video is sponsored by Brilliant. I\'ll start with the elbow, and I seem to be in FK mode, so I\'ll rotate the lower arm. You can also be in IK mode, you just need to see how the elbow looks when you bend the arm to an extreme. So,'

[407:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the problem I see right away is that the elbow is a bit soft. It should be more pointy and protruding. And there is quite a bit of overlap between the lower arm and the upper arm. And this can be'

[407:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fixed very easily with a single shape key. So, let\'s try to implement it. I\'ll go to object mode, select my character, go to data tab, shape keys. A quick reminder of our best practices.'

[407:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You should start working on shape keys when most other aspects of the character are finished, such as modeling, rigging, and weight painting. If you need to do additional weight painting here, please'

[407:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do it before you start working on the shape keys. So, to create my first shape key, I have to press the plus button. That will give me the basis shape key. And by the way, don\'t worry that the rig is currently deforming the character.'

[408:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That is okay. The basis shape key is actually based on the undeformed character. Or in simple terms, adding shape keys is fail-safe. You don\'t have to worry about it too much. And now, I\'ll go right away and add the first'

[408:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actual shape key with the plus button. And let\'s name it CS elbow fix. CS stands for corrective shape. It\'s just a naming convention I like. Let\'s set the shape to one so that I can also edit'

[408:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this shape in sculpt mode. And now with the grab brush, I\'ll start moving the vertices of the elbow and shape them exactly as I want. You can use any shading settings that make working on your character easier.'

[408:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So here I may want to use smoothing in the transition between lower arm and upper arm. And to be more precise, I\'m going to find the smooth brush, go'

[408:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to tool, and set the strength to something low like .2. And then smooth lightly here. Okay, so this is before our shape key'

[409:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and this is after. A significant improvement. Shape keys can be extremely powerful. If you want to edit this shape in edit'

[409:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mode, you\'ll see that the shape looks very weird. I\'ll explain why in a second, but for now go to your character modifiers and make sure that these options on the armature modifier are enabled.'

[409:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now I can go to edit mode and tweak my vertices with even more precision. Okay, I\'ll check my shape, tweak it a little bit more, and I\'ll'

[409:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'call it done. Now if I reset the pose of my rig, you\'ll see that this shape key, which we have enabled now, looks extremely weird. And that is because this shape only'

[410:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'works in the context of the bent arm. Outside of it, it\'s nonsense. But, that\'s okay. We\'re going to make this shape appear only when the character is bending the arm. So, I\'ll set my elbow shape to zero.'

[410:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, the easiest way to apply this shape is if I have an animation of the elbow, I can then also animate the value of this shape key.'

[410:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, that is obviously very impractical. So, we\'re going to create a driver which says, "Whenever the lower arm bends, enable this shape key." And the lower'

[410:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'arm is really perfect for that because it only rotates on a single axis. So, let\'s undo here until I remove the animation. And now, let\'s see how we can create this driver which will trigger the elbow'

[411:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape key when the lower arm is rotated. You already have some experience with drivers, so I recommend stopping and thinking about it for a minute. Okay, we\'re going to want this driver to'

[411:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work in FK mode, but also in IK mode. So, we don\'t want to use any specific FK or IK bones. Let\'s unhide the MCH bones'

[411:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and start the MCH other collection. And this is where we have the MCH lower arm. This is the bone that switches its position depending on whether we are in'

[411:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'IK or FK mode. So, this bone will serve perfectly as our driver. I\'ll switch to rotation and local orientation, and I can see that the rotation axis I\'m looking for is the local X axis. So, we'

[411:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to say, "When this bone is rotating on its local X axis, activate the vertex group." Let\'s go to object mode, select our character, go to data, right click on'

[412:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the value of this vertex group, and add a driver, and then right click again, and open the driver editor. So, we want this value to be driven by the armature, and in particular, the MCH'

[412:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lower arm. r bone. And we\'ll switch type to X rotation in local space. And as soon as we do, our shape key is'

[412:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'going to start taking effect. In fact, it is taking effect too strongly and too fast. So, now we have to tweak that. I\'ll reset the visibility of my rig for'

[412:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now. And it\'s going to be easier to test in FK mode, so I\'ll switch the arm to FK. And I\'ll create a quick test animation again. I\'ll keyframe the lower arm at'

[412:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the default state, and then on frame 20 or so, I\'ll rotate it on the X axis to an extreme, and keyframe again. Let\'s also select these two and press T'

[413:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inside this editor and choose linear. So, let\'s go back to our model and open up the driver editor and see what\'s'

[413:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happening. So, the shape key is driven by the rotation of this bone, and the rotation unit is radians, which I think we'

[413:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'discussed earlier in the course. And here in the value section, you can actually see the conversion. 5° is equal to 0.9. So, by the time I reach 60°, I already'

[413:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'have a value of one, which is the full shape key. What we really want is that this shape key does not really take effect at first, and then only when the lower arm and upper arms start to get'

[413:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'close to each other, then the shape key will kick in. So, one way to kind of achieve this, which you already know, is for example to divide this expression by two. And this will start to look much better.'

[414:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In fact, I could take this as a solution. But, let\'s learn something new about drivers, and that will allow you to control your drivers with a lot of precision. I\'ll set this expression back to just'

[414:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'var. And then, we\'re going to start tweaking this curve here. And I recommend disabling snapping for drivers. With snapping, I can only move this key'

[414:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in increments, which gets a little bit confusing. So, I like to disable it, but the caveat here is that once you\'re done, you should enable it again because this is the same setting for your'

[414:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'animation editors. And when snapping is disabled in the animation editor, you may end up keyframe your character in between frames. With snapping, you will always keyframe at exactly frame 8, 9,'

[415:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '10, 11, and so on. But, without the snapping, you may end up keyframe between these values, which is possible, but generally not what you want. Okay, so now let\'s see how we can tweak this curve. So, we have this test animation,'

[415:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which will help us a lot. And notice how as the lower arm rotates, there is this indicator, which shows us what value we\'re getting for this driver. So, now what I can do is get this first keyframe and rotate it, or I can grab its bezier'

[415:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'handles. And now we have this curve, which starts flat. Which means that there will be very little value change at first. And then the shape key value will start'

[415:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'increasing very quickly. So, let me go all the way to 20 to the full rotation of the arm. At this point, the value is already two, which is way too much. So, I\'ll grab the'

[415:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'second keyframe and press GY and move it down. So, now I can see that the value is around 1.2. So, let me move this further down. And'

[416:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now for this rotation, I\'ll be getting exactly a value of one. Actually, a bit more than one, but our shape keys max is one, so this will work just fine. So, I like this now. I think it looks'

[416:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really nice. But just for practice, I\'ll show you that you can do even more. For example, if you shift and click around here, you can select this curve and press I and choose only selected channel. And that will give you an'

[416:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'additional keyframe. Which you can move. So, for example, I can completely flatten the curve at first. Although, I don\'t like this much, so I\'ll tweak this key lightly.'

[416:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But definitely try to understand this curve because it gives you a lot of power. For example, I can move this keyframe so that the value will increase at first and then decrease again. That'

[416:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
