[424:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to break because the upper arm does not rotate on a single axis. We can also twist it. And now I\'m testing it, and it\'s mostly okay, but in some extreme cases, you may see this weird deformation happening'

[424:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or a sudden flip. That is because we\'re using the Z axis to drive the constraint, but when I twist the upper arm, I can achieve a pose which is technically arm up, but the Z axis is not really doing'

[424:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the raising of the arm. And here, I was going to suggest that we create a whole new bone specifically to drive the shoulder shape key. This bone needs to be oriented the same as our MCH upper arm, but not twist with'

[424:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it. And creating additional bones may be necessary sometimes, but I realized that we already have a bone like that. That is our upper arm twist one. So, let\'s go to the shape key'

[425:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and simply replace the driving bone with MCH upper arm twist one.r. So, now I can try twisting this arm in'

[425:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'very extreme poses, but my shape key is very stable. As a reminder, our first twist bone here has copy location and damped track with head tail set to one so that it points'

[425:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'towards the tail of the bone. It also has copy rotation set to a very low value, almost negligible. So, if you had to create this additional bone specifically for driving the shoulder shape key, then you would have created'

[425:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it with copy location and damp track. And I said that we should enable snapping for the animation editors once we are done with the drivers. The reason is, if I disable snapping and'

[425:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I zoom in, see how I can move this frame between the keyframes. And that can cause a lot of trouble. So, let\'s undo it and enable snapping, and now the frame will snap to the keyframes.'

[426:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, I\'ll reset the rig and unlink the action. So, this is it. This is all you need to'

[426:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know to create shape keys with a lot of control. The examples of the elbow and knee are the more common ones, and with the shoulder we also covered quite a complex one. So, I\'m happy to move forward to the shape key face rig.'

[426:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Welcome to this video on Blender face rigging using a combination of bones and shape keys. This is probably the only complete guide of this kind on YouTube.'

[426:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This video is part of my course rigging isn\'t scary. So, if you found it randomly, you maybe wondering, can I follow it without the rest of the course? The short answer is yes. If you have enough basic rigging knowledge, you'

[426:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can. I\'d recommend checking out the video on shape key basics if you\'re new to the subject. So, let\'s dive in. It\'s a long video, but it covers a lot of ground. Shape keys offer a number of advantages when it comes to face'

[427:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rigging. They are easier to create, more reliable, and more artistic. And most importantly, they can produce high-quality results from hobby films to massive Hollywood productions, shape'

[427:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keys have been the industry standard in face rigging. Probably the most important consideration now is what shapes should we build? There is no single right answer here, but I\'m going'

[427:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to suggest two main approaches. First, if you want to use facial mocap, I recommend looking up the 52 ARKit shapes. You can find detailed guides about them online, and you can sculpt'

[427:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and name your shape keys according to these guides. Then you can use apps to record and retarget the facial animation. That is not the focus of this course, but I wanted to mention it'

[427:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quickly in case it\'s something you\'re interested in exploring. The approach we are going to use instead is based on the book Stop Staring, which is a highly respected guide to facial rigging. We\'ll build the essential shapes recommended'

[428:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in that book. Here is a list of the shapes we\'ll be building, and you can animate the whole face using shape keys. But for some parts, especially the jaw and eyes, using bones may actually be better. And because the goal of this'

[428:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'course is to maximize learning, we\'re going to go for this approach and learn a lot in the process. And to not just maximize, but supercharge your learning, check out Skillshare, an online learning'

[428:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'platform with thousands of classes made specifically for creatives like you. Skillshare is kindly sponsoring this video. My content is all about rigging, so if you\'re looking to expand your'

[428:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'skills with related topics like animation, or maybe character modeling, or even character design, Skillshare is a great place to explore. I\'ve been diving into Unreal Engine lately, and I'

[429:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like how Skillshare brings together everything from blueprints to visual effects, all in one place and available on demand. Personally, I\'m interested in using Unreal for cinematics, not for'

[429:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'games. So I\'m currently working through some in-depth courses by 3D College. I also have a great playlist of other Unreal classes lined up. The first 500 people to use my link in the description'

[429:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will receive 20% off their first year of Skillshare. Get started today. And now let\'s get back to facial rigging with shape keys. So first we\'re going to focus on rigging the jaw, eyes, and even'

[429:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the tongue using bones. Okay, now we\'re going to create the bones that we need for the bone portion of our face rig. And that will be a jaw bone, two eye bones, and a chain of three bones for'

[429:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the tongue. Let\'s go to edit mode. Shift A to create a new bone. I\'ll call it jaw for now. And place it in the jaw of the'

[430:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character. I\'m paying special attention to this point, which will become the pivot point of the jaw. Now I\'ll create a copy of this bone.'

[430:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Place it where the tongue is and call it tongue one. And then extrude two more bones all the way to the tip of the tongue.'

[430:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And let\'s name these bones tongue two and tongue three. Create a copy of one of the bones.'

[430:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In global orientation, I\'ll press S then Z then zero to straighten it. And this will be the eye bone. Let\'s call it eye.l. I\'ll go to my mesh edit mode.'

[430:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And alt and click on this loop, which is the middle of the eye. Then press shift S, cursor to selected. Back to my rig. Select the eye bone, shift S, selection to cursor. And now the bone is exactly'

[431:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the middle of the eye. Right click and symmetrize it. Okay, now these bones will be our deforming bones. So, let\'s select all of them. Edit, batch rename,'

[431:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'switch to bones, set name prefix d e f dash. And then press M and move them to the d e f collection. Start the d e f collection and I want to'

[431:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parent these bones logically. So, I\'ll select the jaw and the two eyes and shift select the head, control P keep offset. And then select the tongue and shift select the jaw, control P keep offset.'

[431:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And as we learned in the chapter about organizing our rig, we want to create copies of these bones and constrain the deforming bones to them. We don\'t want any parenting between the deforming bones and the rest of the rig.'

[432:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, select the new bones, shift D, duplicate them, and let\'s press M and create a new bone collection for now and just call it face.'

[432:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, in pose mode, we\'re going to give copy transforms constraint to our deforming bones. Right, we are in the d e f collection now.'

[432:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then set target to armature. Shift select the rest of the bones, pose, constraints, copy constraints, and then I have to set the target of the jaw'

[432:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to be the jaw 001 bone. rename these bones in a second. Okay, that\'s it for the d e f bones.'

[432:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s unstart them. Now, all of these bone copies will become m c h bones. So, let\'s name them appropriately. Batch rename, bones, find and replace,'

[433:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'find d e f and replace with m c h. And then one more time, find .001 and replace with nothing to remove the .001 suffix.'

[433:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And these MCH bones are still parented to the DEF head. That\'s not a huge problem, but I\'m going to parent them to the head bone. So, select them, shift'

[433:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the head bone, edit mode, control P keep offset. And the tongue is parented to the MCH jaw, which looks fine to me. Next, we\'re going to set up the weights. But before that, I\'m going to separate'

[433:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the face from the body. It\'s really cool that we can do that in Blender without too much worry. So, I\'ll just select some polygons roughly and then press control L, selecting the whole face with the eyes,'

[433:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'teeth, and so on. P and separate selection. Next, I\'ll go to data and delete all shapes. I don\'t need these shapes for the face. They only affect the body.'

[434:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then, I\'ll go to edit mode again, select only the face with L, and separate it. Then, I\'ll select the eye and separate it. And then the right eye and separate it as well.'

[434:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, now we have the face, each eye, and the teeth as a separate object. Now, select the rig, go to pose mode, and let\'s start the face collection'

[434:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because I forgot to disable the deform option from the MCH bones. Select them all, untick deform, right click, and copy to selected. Next,'

[434:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll select all of these face parts, but not the body. Shift select the rig, control P, and parent with empty groups to add the new groups like jaw, eyes, and so on. Let\'s go to the eye, select all'

[435:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vertices, go to vertex groups, find the d e f i.l group and click assign. Then on the other eye, select all vertices, find i.r and assign. To weight the jaw, I\'m going to select'

[435:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the face, go to edit mode, select one of the central vertices on the lips and press control plus to expand the selection until I have the whole mouth covered.'

[435:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then in side view, toggle x-ray and select all jaw vertices like this. Next, I\'ll go to weight paint,'

[435:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select the jaw vertex group, enable vertex selection. I\'ll check my paint settings. Set blend to add. Strength can be kept to a high value.'

[436:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I don\'t need mirroring, but I do need auto normalize. And then I\'ll just paint on these vertices that I selected. I can also enable projected here and disable front faces only'

[436:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to make sure I\'m getting all of the vertices including the occluded ones. Then shift and click to smooth these weights.'

[436:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now let\'s test the jaw. That is not too bad. I\'m going to open the mouth'

[436:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and go back to weight paint mode, disable vertex selection, and start smoothing the edge of the mouth. &gt;&gt; This is looking good. We\'re going to'

[437:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'take care of the teeth as well. But let\'s test the eyes. I need to switch to bounding box center and rotate them around. Okay, it looks like the eyes are also'

[437:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'weighted to the head. That is why we\'re getting slightly weird deformations here. So, let\'s fix it in one of the ways we know. I\'ll select a vertex here, then press L to select all other vertices, set DEF head to zero, and press copy.'

[437:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And let\'s do the same for the other eye. Now, the rotation of the eye is good, but the problem is that we have half an eye. So, at a very extreme rotation, we'

[437:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of see the end of the eye. So, I\'ll go and do some quick modeling here. I\'ll just extrude some edges and scale them.'

[437:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That will be enough. Same on the other side. Okay, now the eyes are looking fine.'

[438:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The teeth are already fully weighted to the head. So, what I need to do is weight the lower part of the teeth to the jaw bone. Let\'s select the teeth first.'

[438:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'From this menu, remove from all groups, find DEF jaw, and click assign. And I can press H to hide them. Now, I\'m going to select a central'

[438:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vertex on the lower part of the gums and start pressing control plus to expand the selection to about here. Then, I\'ll remove from all groups, select the DEF jaw group and assign.'

[438:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In weight paint mode, I can smooth a bit. I can set smooth to an even higher value.'

[439:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, now all we have to do is take care of the tongue. Let\'s go to edit mode, select the central vertex and start expanding the selection to about here and then remove from all'

[439:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'groups. Next, I\'ll go to my rig and let\'s just isolate the rig and the teeth.'

[439:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
