[439:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then I\'m going to select the tongue bones. Go to object mode, shift select the teeth, go to weight paint mode, enable vertex selection and go to weights assign automatic from bones. This will'

[440:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'assign the selected tongue vertices to the selected tongue bones. Disable vertex selection and check the weights. Some smoothing will probably be needed,'

[440:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but this was an efficient and precise way to add weights to these teeth. Let\'s unstart the DEF.'

[440:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now I can test the deformations of the tongue. Some smoothing will be needed here.'

[440:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; By the way, if your teeth are missing'

[441:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'textures like mine here, select the teeth object, go to shading, select the gums material, find the UV map node,'

[441:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'select map one from it, and just plug it into all of the textures. Okay, now that everything is weighted'

[441:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'nicely, we can start building some mechanisms. Let\'s unstart the EF and reset the rig.'

[441:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now we\'ll create an eye setup similar to that in level two. Let\'s go to edit mode. Select the two eye bones. Shift E, duplicate them, and move them on the Y axis.'

[442:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll name this bone eye target.l and the other one eye target.r. In pose mode, select one eye target and your'

[442:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'respective eye, control shift C damp track. Now the eye bone points to the target. Let\'s do the same on the other side. Select the eye target, shift select the eye, control shift C damp track.'

[442:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now in edit mode, duplicate one of the bones, move it on the X axis, and under item set head to zero and tail X to zero. That places this bone exactly in the'

[442:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'center of the world. Let\'s make it a little bit bigger and call it eye master and parent the two targets to it. Now this bone moves both eyes,'

[442:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but we can also move the individual targets. This eye setup may actually be a little bit better and a little bit easier than the one we did in level two. The jaw we can just rotate around if we'

[443:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wanted to, but here is something else we can do. I\'ll go to edit mode with individual origins, scale the jaw a little bit bigger, then select the tail of the jaw bone, press E and Z to extrude another bone,'

[443:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'alt P and clear parent, and let\'s name this bone jaw master. In pose mode, select the jaw master, shift select the jaw bone, control shift'

[443:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'C dump truck. Now I have this jaw control which I can control by moving instead of rotating. And before I forget, let me parent this jaw master to the head.'

[443:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Control P keep offset. Here when I rotate the head, I\'m'

[443:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'noticing some problems. It seems to be because some of the surrounding bones are affecting the jaw area. So let\'s go to the rig, start a DEF collection, shift select the'

[444:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'face mesh, go to weight paint mode, alt and click on the jaw to select it. And with a paintbrush set up like this, we\'ll just control and click to paint out the influence.'

[444:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The chest bone also affects the jaw a little bit and also the shoulders. So I\'m just removing all of these unnecessary weights. And the problem is solved.'

[444:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now shift select the head and smooth a little bit in this area, and also a little bit of smoothing for the jaw. And this should be good. Our jaw and eyes are looking good. Let\'s'

[444:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'give them some shapes. For the eye master, I\'m going to use the rectangle and orient it. For the eye targets, let\'s use a circle.'

[445:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Looking good. And for the jaw, we could use another circle.'

[445:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You\'ll notice that you can kind of disconnect the circle, but we can use override transform and make it stick to the MCH jaw. At first, it will place it all the way'

[445:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here, but then I can slide it on the Y axis. And now the control will look a lot more stable. Next, we\'re going to work on the tongue, and this is going to be very cool'

[445:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because we\'re going to implement some squash and stretch mechanisms, which we haven\'t done so far. Let\'s reset the rig and isolate it. Go to edit mode and I\'ll hide the jaw'

[445:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so that I can focus on the tongue bones. I\'ll select the connection between the first and second tongue bones, press E and Z, and extrude a new bone, and alt P, and clear the parent. And let\'s name'

[446:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this bone tongue control one. Then, with vertex snapping, I\'m going to duplicate this bone and snap it at the next intersection, and then shift D and'

[446:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'snap this copy at the tip of the tongue. Let\'s name these bones tongue control two and tongue control three. Now, in pose mode,'

[446:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll hide the jaw, and I\'m going to make this main tongue bone stretch to the position of of the control bone. So, I\'ll select the control bone, shift select the tongue bone, control shift C, and for squash'

[446:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and stretch, we have a constraint called stretch two. So, let\'s enable it, and now if I move this bone, you\'ll see the constraint bone squashing and stretching. The'

[446:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'remaining bones are also squashing and stretching with it because of parenting. So, let\'s just repeat this setup for the remaining bones. With this control selected, shift select the tongue bone, control shift C, stretch two, and one'

[447:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more time here. And now we have this stretchy chain. This is the basis for squash and stretch chains in Blender. Now, let\'s go out of local mode and test this.'

[447:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, now if I open the jaw, the tongue is not moving with it. So, let\'s isolate again, go to edit mode, alt H to unhide the jaw, select all of these control bones, shift select the'

[447:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'jaw, control P, keep offset. Now, the control bones will move with the jaw, and therefore, the tongue will move with the jaw. And now I can grab these controls here,'

[447:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and I can pose the tongue in pretty much any shape I want. And this is a nice setup, but we can improve it a little bit. Let\'s isolate again. Reset the rig.'

[447:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Select the tip control and shift select the next control, control shift C, and give it copy transforms. Switch target and owner to local space. And let\'s do the exact same setup for'

[448:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the other control. Control shift C, copy transforms, local space and local space. Now, when I move this control, the other ones move with it, and now if I just play with the influence, I\'ll set this one to'

[448:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '.5 or so, and the next one to .25, and this gives me this nice automatic stretching of the tongue. Okay, so that means that I can pose this'

[448:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tongue by just moving this one single control. Occasionally, I may want to move the other ones. I should switch to a different mix mode'

[448:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'such as after original. Okay, this gives us really good control over the tongue.'

[449:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let\'s set up the shapes. For the tip, I\'m going to use the curvy shape and adjust it. And for the additional controls, I\'ll'

[449:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use the sphere. Let\'s set some bone colors as well. And make the wire width thicker.'

[449:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The eye bones may be too close, which means that the eyes react too quickly. So, let\'s go to edit mode and offset them a bit.'

[449:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Yeah, this feels nice. And with that, our bone setup for the face is done. Let\'s move on to the shape keys.'

[450:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'ll create a highly optimized set of 16 or so shapes, but the cool thing about these limited number of shapes is that they will allow you to create lip sync and show major human emotions. And'

[450:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they also work for a variety of styles from realistic to cartoony and anime. Again, these shapes are based on the book Stop Staring with slight modifications from me just so that we'

[450:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can learn some cool tricks. So, step one, let\'s create these shapes. And some of them need to be split into left and right side, but we\'ll model and sculpt the shapes with symmetry first, and then'

[450:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll show you a trick how to get the right side and left side separated automatically. So, I\'ll select a face model, go to data, press the plus button to create the'

[451:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basis key, and one more time to create our first key. And first we\'ll be working on a shape called mouth wide. And before we start, let me share the main modeling techniques I\'ll be using'

[451:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because creating the shapes is just a lot of vertex pushing. So, there will be a lot of time lapses where I\'m just using the same techniques over and over. I can tweak the mesh in edit mode, and when I do, I\'ll definitely want to'

[451:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'use symmetry. So, let\'s go to N panel tool, and we can enable mirror here. And if our character is perfectly symmetrical, just moving one side will also affect the other. And of course, we'

[451:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t want to move one vertex at a time. So, a big help here is the proportional editing tool. When I enable it, I can move large portions of the mesh at the same time. Now, right now this is too much, so I'

[451:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need to scroll the mouse wheel up to lessen the effect to only the mouth area. By default, proportional editing will affect all vertices near the selected one. But if you press Alt O,'

[452:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then you can make proportional editing affect only connected vertices. And that can be very useful in areas like the mouth, so that I can only affect the upper lip and not the lower lip. So,'

[452:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s more or less all I\'m going to be doing in edit mode. But actually, most of the time I\'ll use sculpt mode. Sculpt mode is really nice because even if the topology of your character is not'

[452:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'symmetrical, the symmetry in sculpt mode will still work. Don\'t forget that if you want to create a shape key in sculpt mode, you have to make sure that the active shape key is set to one. If it\'s set to zero, then nothing will'

[452:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happen when you try to sculpt. So, set it to one. And I\'ll mainly be using the move brush. Occasionally, I may want to lightly smooth something, but by default, the smooth brush is way too strong. So,'

[452:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'activate the smooth brush, and by default, it will be set to 0.7 or so. I\'ll set it to 0.2. It kind of depends on your mesh density. My character is quite low poly, so I'

[453:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'need a very low value here. The default behavior of the grab brush is that it will move unconnected geometry. If you want to avoid this, enable the auto masking topology option, and now as'

[453:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'long as you\'re not too close to the other surface or you don\'t use too big of a brush, this will only affect the connected geometry. Other than that, I might use inflate and'

[453:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'decrease brush occasionally. And I believe those are all of the techniques that I\'ll be using while creating shape keys. Oh, and one more tip, go to end panel view and set focal length to something much higher than 50.'

[453:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Something around 85 or so. It will give you a more natural and less distorted view of your character. One final tip that has nothing to do with Blender, get a little mirror that you can set on your desk and observe your'

[453:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'own face while creating the shapes. Now, let\'s hide the rig and disable wireframe. And we can start sculpting our first shape, mouth wide. Okay, so mouth wide'

[454:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will be slightly special. It\'s not a real expression. It\'s just a mouth stretching sideways without really creating a smile or any other special emotion. So, of course, I can stretch it'

[454:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sideways, but keep in mind that the teeth have a horseshoe shape. So, the mouth doesn\'t really just go sideways. It also moves back at the same time. In solid shading and using x-ray, we can'

[454:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'actually see the teeth. Although, I won\'t be using that. So, from this angle, I\'m going to stretch the mouth like this. Something like this. Don\'t worry too'

[454:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much about this initial shape. We\'ll very likely have to go back and fix these shapes as we try to combine them with other shapes. And speaking of combining shapes, the next shape will be the smile. And we\'re going to do'

[455:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something special with it. We\'re going to use this initial mouth wide shape as a base for the smile. So, let\'s create a new shape. Call it mouth smile and set it to one. And do not set mouth wide to zero yet.'

[455:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Make sure that mouth smile is enabled. And let\'s try to shape this mouth into something that looks more like a smile. So, I\'ll mainly raise the corners of the'

[455:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mouth to make it more like a smile, but I\'m not going to affect the wideness of the mouth too much because that is controlled by the mouth wide. Also, I should set my auto masking topology off because I don\'t want to'

[455:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open and close the lips here. I just want to pull the entire mouth up and down. Something like this. And an important'

[456:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'point is that the smile will also affect the cheeks. It will raise and kind of puff them out a little bit. So, I\'ll raise the cheeks slightly and then with the inflate brush, puff them out a'

[456:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little bit. Also, all the way here, and that will make the smile a little bit more genuine. It won\'t look very genuine yet because it\'s just a mouth, but really a genuine smile involves showing a little bit of the teeth and also'

[456:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'squinting a little bit. Just the smile will look kind of weird.'

[456:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We have to combine it with the wide, but when we build the interface for the face, you\'ll see how it will be very easy to control. Okay, so this was a special technique and we kind of started with the most difficult thing in this'

[456:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'section. Okay, now let\'s set wide and smile all the way to zero and create a new shape and that will be our mouth frown. Set it to one and sculpt it. Frown is a lot easier to create than the'

[457:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'smile. I guess as humans we pay a lot more attention to what a genuine smile is, whereas with the frown, if we just move the edges of the mouth down a little'

[457:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bit, it kind of looks like it. One thing you can do is use the inflate brush to puff out the area just below and around the edge of the mouth. Or you could use another brush as well.'

[457:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Oh wow, this is way too strong. Okay, this will be our frown. Let\'s set frown to zero and create the'

[457:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'next shape. Mouth narrow, which will be kind of the opposite of our mouth wide. Set it to one and start sculpting. So, as the name suggests, we\'ll make the'

[458:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mouth narrower. The lips are a muscle. They have volume. So, when the mouth becomes narrower, the'

[458:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lips will kind of become a little bit taller and they will poke out. So, this shape can also be called pucker or a kissy mouth. And the mouth gets this kind of diamond'

[458:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape. I can use topology masking to separate the lips very, very slightly. Okay, let\'s move on.'

[459:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Set all shapes to zero and next we\'ll do upper lip up. This shape raises the upper lip of the'

[459:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'character and for it, definitely use auto masking or in edit mode, use the hollow circle for proportional editing. And I want to move the upper lip like'

[459:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this, exposing the teeth up to around the gums. Okay, this should be a good base. We might tweak it later, but let\'s move on to the next shape, which is the'

[459:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'opposite, lower lip down. Which will be something like this.'

[459:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Again, lower lip going down to the gum level. Next, we\'ll do upper lip in. And for this shape, I\'m going to use'

[460:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'edit mode. I think it\'s a little bit easier because I have to rotate the upper lip and kind of tuck it in under the upper teeth. So, I\'ll select these vertices'

[460:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and use proportional editing. I\'ll rotate the lip and then move it around here under the teeth. Now, here in edit mode, I\'ll select the'

[460:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lower lip and hide it and then go to sculpt mode. That way, I can keep sculpting the upper lip without affecting the lower lip. Here, I really want to focus only on the upper lip. Okay, so the upper lip will go in and it'

[460:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will look very, very thin from the outside. Just press Alt H. And yeah, this is more or less what I\'m'

[461:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'looking for. Let\'s make the next shape, which will be lower lip in. So, the same thing for the lower lip. It\'s a good idea to test both upper lip'

[461:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and lower lip in. They should look good together. If you want to edit them in this state, make sure that you are selecting the shape that you actually want to edit.'

[461:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, now I\'m editing the lower lip. And now the upper lip. Okay, these shapes are important for'

[462:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'various things, especially for lipsync for sounds like F, B, M, and so on. And hey, we\'re all done with the lip shapes.'

[462:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here we may want to reorder these shapes so that the upper lip shapes are next to each other. So, I\'ll select upper lip in and press the up arrow. That will move it up and it\'s just for'

[462:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'organizational purposes and it doesn\'t change anything in our shapes. Here might be a good idea to test some of the shapes. Let\'s try to create a smile and also open the mouth and that should start to create a more natural smile. If'

[462:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it doesn\'t, you can select the shape that you need to tweak. Here I believe it\'s the smile that needs to be tweaked a little bit. And I can tweak it until it looks good'

[462:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'with this combination of shapes that I expect to use. I may want to tweak the wide a little bit to make it follow the teeth a little bit more and the smile to go up a little bit'

[463:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more. And this kind of tweaks will make a big difference in the final quality of your shapes because they need to combine well together. But for now, we\'ll move on to other'

[463:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shapes. First, we\'ll create the closing of the eyes. So, let\'s create a new shape. Call it eyes closed. And here we can use masking'

[463:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to mask out the brows. If masking is not visible, you can it here. All right, and now with the grab brush,'

[463:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I can start closing the eyes. When the eye closes, it\'s mostly the'

[464:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'upper eyelid that does the closing, but there is a little bit of lower eyelid movement as well. You can also make this into two separate shapes. That is up to you. Here, I\'ll keep it a little bit simpler and use one shape to close both the upper eyelid and the lower eyelid.'

[464:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll smooth out the wireframe a little bit. And make sure the eye closes all the'

[464:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way. Okay, good. This should do.'

[464:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll press Alt M to remove the mask. We\'re very close now. We just need some brows shapes and a couple of other subtle shapes around the face. The next shape will be brows up.'

[465:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And here again, I\'ll use masking to mask the eyelids because I only want to affect the eyebrows. And now we\'ll start raising the eyebrow'

[465:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'favoring the outside because there will be another shape favoring the inner side of the eyebrow. With the eyebrow, it\'s important to keep'

[465:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in mind that there is the skull under it. So, take that into consideration. The next shape will be brows down.'

[465:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And sometimes with these kind of opposite shapes, you can actually set range men to minus one and set the value to minus one and see if it works well. In this case, I don\'t think that is what'

[466:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we\'re looking for because there is skull here and the brows kind of need to go sideways a little bit. So, I\'ll set this to zero and range men to zero. And let\'s create the next shape and call it brows'

[466:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'down. Set it to one and sculpt it. Something like this. Next, we\'ll do the'

[466:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inner part of the brows. Again, they can go up and down. And the inner part of the brows actually'

[466:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'convey a lot of emotion. You can see by just creating this shape, our character starts to look kind of sad. And here, I think we may be able to use'

[467:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the range men to create the inner down shape. So, let\'s set range men to minus one and set the value to minus one. And again, see how right away the character kind of looks angry. So, if that looks'

[467:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'perfect to you, you could just use the negative value, but here we\'re going to do something else. Make sure that only brow inner up is set to minus one and everything else is zero and then go to this menu and create new shape from mix.'

[467:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This will basically duplicate whatever shapes we have into a new shape. Now, I\'ll set brows inner up to zero. Set range min to zero as well and enable this new shape.'

[467:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And that will be the base for my brows inner down. So, now I\'ll just tweak it a little bit. Having it as a separate shape gives me'

[468:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more control. Okay, something like this. The next shape is brow squeeze.'

[468:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is a subtle shape in which the brows kind of come together and it tends to convey thinking. You may'

[468:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not see much of a difference here for two reasons. First, the shape is subtle, but second, it\'s not so much the movement of the brows as there are some subtle that appear on the character.'

[468:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, we\'ll finish up with two more subtle shapes. One will be called sneer. And that is probably exactly as you imagine it, kind of moving the nostrils up and conveying disgust or anger.'

[468:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, raise the nose and the surrounding areas and maybe puff them out a little bit.'

[469:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And finally, we\'ll do a squint.'

[469:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In the squint, the lower eyelids will move up. But actually, this is driven by moving the facial muscles below the eyelid up.'

[469:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You may want to create a crease here and puff out the lower eyelid a little bit. Here I\'m dealing with very little'

[469:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'polygons, so I cannot really do that. A little bit of a squint combined with a'

[470:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'smile can give a more genuine smile. And these will be our basic shapes. Of course, keep tweaking your shapes as much as needed until you get the kind of results that you want. I\'m sure many of'

[470:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you are better artists than me and you will achieve better results by spending more time tweaking your shapes. But now we\'ll move on to creating the left and right side of the shapes that need that. And that is extremely easy to do. Shape'

[470:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keys have a vertex group, so we\'ll just create a vertex group splitting the face into two halves and we\'ll use it to extract left side and right side for each shape.'

[470:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So let\'s see which shapes will need that. All mouth shapes except for narrow will need it. So I\'ll name each shape with the dot L suffix first. Actually, the lower lip and upper lip in'

[471:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'will not need symmetry, so we\'ll leave them without a suffix. Eyes closed and the brow shapes will need dot L. But the squeeze does not need it.'

[471:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Snear will need it and squint also. Okay, now let\'s go to edit mode, isolate the face, use solid shading mode and x-ray, and select exactly one half of the mesh.'

[471:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'By the way, an easy way to do this is to select the central point, go to select side of active. So, this selected the left side of the'

[471:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'face. So, I\'ll create a new vertex group and call it shape key left. With a weight of one, click assign. Now, press control I'

[471:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and control plus to select the whole right side, create a new shape, call it shape key right, and assign.'

[472:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then, switch to weight paint mode, and for each of these shape keys, I\'ll go to weights, smooth, and iteration can be one or two at most. Let\'s do the same here.'

[472:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, now we can go to the shape keys, and for each shape that needs left and right side, here are the steps that we\'re going to take. Enable that shape key and only that'

[472:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape key. From this menu, use new shape from mix. And because we only have one shape activated, this will essentially duplicate the shape key. Let\'s move the two copies together, copy'

[472:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this name, paste it here, and replace it with {dot}r. And in the {dot} l one, use vertex group shape key left. And for the right one, we\'ll use shape'

[473:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'key right. And now the {dot} r shape key controls the right side of the face, and the {dot} l shape key controls the left side of the face. So, let\'s repeat this for all shapes that need left side'

[473:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and right side. I\'m sure there must be a script somewhere to do this automatically, but in this course, we\'re doing everything manually in order to learn. One pitfall to watch out for is that you'

[473:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'may just select a shape and try to duplicate it using new shape from mix, but that is not how it works. What you duplicate is the exact shape that you have active, so you have to set only one shape to one and then do new shape from'

[474:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mix. Good job going through this whole'

[474:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'process. Now we are getting to the exciting part, creating the face interface, which will allow us to tweak and animate these shapes in a very intuitive way. While it is possible to animate by just dragging these sliders'

[474:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here, it\'s really not a great idea because usually we\'ll be animating the rig. So if I want to tweak the shape keys, I would have to switch to the head model and tweak them here. So what else'

[475:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can we do? Another possibility would be to use properties again, but as the number of properties grows, this area gets cluttered and it will get almost as difficult to work with that as with the'

[475:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape key values here. So, instead, we\'re going to create an interface using bones right inside our rig. Let\'s go to edit mode for the rig and'

[475:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'create a new bone. This will be just a quick demonstration. Let\'s call this bone shape key control or something like that. And let\'s say that by sliding this bone'

[475:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'on the X axis, we want to activate the mouth smile shape key. We could right click on the X location value, copy as new driver, go to our head, go to mouth wide L, right click and'

[475:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'paste as new driver. Now, if I slide this bone on the X axis, you\'ll see how it activates the shape.'

[476:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if I give it a circle widget, and lock most of the transforms,'

[476:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I could also duplicate this bone, and shape it like this, and lock all of its axis, and now this whole thing becomes like a bit of an interface.'

[476:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We could also free up the Y axis, and copy it as a new driver, and paste that into the smile.'

[476:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, moving this control up will activate the smile, and sideways makes the mouth wider. So, that\'s definitely a step in the'

[477:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right direction, but instead of creating these joystick-like interfaces, which are quite popular, and you could use them for other purposes. In fact, you could replace these properties here with sliders like that. So, they\'re'

[477:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'definitely useful, but for the face, we could add bones right in the face in the area that they affect and make controllers out of that, and that will be so much more intuitive. So, this was just to show you the basic'

[477:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'principle and a way to create rig interfaces. I hope it\'s useful. But now we\'re going to delete these bones, and we\'re going to start creating the actual interface right on the face. So, let\'s start by placing the 3D cursor'

[477:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at corner and shift A and create a new bone. With individual origin, scale it down. And let\'s name all of these interface'

[477:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bones with the SK prefix. So, something like SK mouth corner.l. And this bone is going to control the wide smile and frown of the character.'

[478:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, I\'m going to duplicate this bone, place the cursor around here, shift S selection to cursor. And let\'s name this bone SK upper lip up.l.'

[478:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I\'ll place another one at the lower lip. And I can press alt F to flip this bone. This will make it so moving it in this direction gives us positive Y values for the bone, and that will make it slightly'

[478:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'easier to set up the driver for the shape. This is lower lip down.l. Now, I\'ll place the 3D cursor here in'

[478:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the center and go to view, 3D cursor, and place it exactly at X0, and press shift A to add another bone. Scale it down, bring it out a bit, and'

[479:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'let\'s call this one just mouth. Okay, now I\'ll add a bone here for the sneer. So, let\'s call it SK sneer.l.'

[479:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'One at the eyelid for closing the eyelid. One bone in the middle of the brow.'

[479:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I named it just brow.l. And one at the inner edge and let\'s name it inner brow.l.'

[479:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'For the brow squeeze, I want a bone right here in the center between the eyebrows. So, I\'ll duplicate this bone, right click to cancel the movement, and then bring this bone up because it\'s already in the center.'

[480:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And that will be a brow squeeze. I\'m checking what other bones we need.'

[480:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We need one around here for the squint. And two more bones, one at the upper lip'

[480:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for the upper lip in action. And one below it for the lower lip in. And I\'ll flip this bone because for this'

[480:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape, I\'m going to want to move the bone down. Okay, I believe this will do. So, let\'s select all bones that need a right'

[480:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'counterpart. Right click and symmetrize them. And then select all of these new bones. And parent them to the head bone.'

[481:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Actually, the bones at the corner and at the lower lip will move down with the'

[481:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'jaw, so I\'m going to parent them to the jaw. It will make our rig more intuitive. Now, I\'ll select all of these new bones'

[481:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and give them a simple circle shape. I\'ll make the shapes a little bit'

[481:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'smaller. And only the mouth one, I\'m going to make a little bit bigger and stretch it a bit like this to indicate that this is the mouth control. I forgot to add the dot L suffix to the'

[482:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'squint, so now I\'m fixing that and symmetrizing the bone. Okay, again, let\'s start with the most difficult area and that will be the mouth corner.'

[482:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll go to my head mesh and remove these drivers by right clicking and choosing delete driver. And now, let\'s add a driver for mouth wide dot L and again, right click and open'

[482:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the driver editor. I\'ll set my object to be the armature. And the bone that will be driving this is the mouth corner dot L.'

[482:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can select this bone, enable the move gizmo, and switch to local orientation, and that will tell you the axis of the bones. So, for the stretch,'

[483:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we want to use the X axis, and for the smile, the Y axis, and for the frown, we\'re going to actually use the negative Y axis. So, as you see, we have a lot less controls than shape keys. That is'

[483:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because we can control multiple shape keys with one control, which is not only efficient, but also very intuitive. So, X location here is good. We just need to switch to local space.'

[483:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now we can actually test the shape. Now, the problem is, if you zoom in, you\'ll you\'ll see that the driver already works, but I need to move this control a couple of meters to activate'

[483:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the whole shape. You should already know how to solve this. In fact, you should know two ways. One will be to multiply the variable. Here, we\'re going to need a large value'

[483:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like 100. So, now moving the control to here activates the full shape key. I may want to go to 120 or so. Yeah, this is looking nice.'

[484:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, instead of this, we could move the shape to around here, which is where I want the full shape key to be activated. And then I\'ll go to the face, set this expression to just var,'

[484:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then grab the second key frame and press G and Y and start moving it up. And I\'m going to have to move it up quite a bit. I can do a G Y and then type 100 on the'

[484:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'numpad. And that wasn\'t quite enough, so I\'ll keep moving it to here. Okay, good. Okay, now we can go ahead and set up'

[484:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'smile.l. I can actually copy this driver and paste it into smile.l, and then open the driver editor. And for smile.l, I just want to switch type to Y location.'

[484:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And it will probably work right away. So, now I can stretch the mouth and enable a smile. And for the frown, I should be able to'

[485:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'just copy this driver, paste it into frown L. Now, if we test this, something weird will happen and I recommend stopping the'

[485:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'video and trying to figure out what happened. Okay, so what happened is we have the exact same driver for smile L and frown L. And when I move this control up, it activates both shape keys. But smile and'

[485:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frown are not supposed to be added together. It\'s super easy to fix this. Just open the driver editor and for frown L, set the expression to minus var. Now, moving the bone up in the Y'

[485:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'direction produces positive values, so it only activates the smile. For the frown, it actually produces a minus one value, but a frown is clipped between zero and one.'

[486:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, for anything less than zero, we just get a zero value. And vice versa for the frown, and that is how we got this intuitive mouth corner control.'

[486:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, there are some things that we may want to change. This control is not meant to be rotated or scaled, and it only moves on the Y and Z axis. So, we\'re going to lock all of these'

[486:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'axis. In fact, let\'s select all of these controls. And I\'m going to hold alt and lock these axis. If alt clicking doesn\'t work for you, as always, you can use right click'

[486:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and copy all to select it. Now, all of these are locked, so as I work with these controls, I\'ll unlock only the transforms that I want. And again, let\'s select all of these controls.'

[486:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And finally, I\'ll shift select the corner one. And I\'ll give it a limit location constraint. Tick affect transform and choose local space. And I\'ll also'

[487:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'activate all limits. And then go to pose constraints, copy constraints to selected bones. So, now all of the bones will have this constraint. And then, as I set them up, I\'m going to tweak the settings.'

[487:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, now for this bone, I want to unlock X and Y. And a value of point .54 or so activates the full wide. So, let\'s set maximum to'

[487:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this value. Y of 0.8 or so activates the full smile. So, let\'s paste it into the maximum Y'

[487:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'value. And minus the same value will be perfect for the frown. And now, if I activate this constraint, which I had disabled, the control will only move within these limits.'

[488:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'If I go to edit mode and symmetrize this bone, it will actually symmetrize the constraint, which gives me perfect limits for the bone on the other side.'

[488:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, let\'s just set up the right side of the face in the same way. I\'ll just copy and paste the driver and edit it to use the opposite bone.'

[488:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This will almost work, but the X axis is'

[488:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inverted on the other side. So, for the mouth wide.r, I need to set the expression to minus bar. Okay, this was by far the most difficult'

[489:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'setup. Now, let\'s set up some of the easier ones like the mouth, sneer, and so on. They will just move in a single direction. So, we\'ll set up upper lip up together and then as a challenge, you\'ll'

[489:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do the rest yourself. Let\'s add a driver. Open the driver editor. Object is the armature.'

[489:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The bone is upper lip up.l. Type Y location. If you need to check, go to your bone and unlock the location transforms.'

[489:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, here I want the Y. So, type Y location and local space. I\'ll set Y maximum to 0.05'

[489:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'or 0.8 or so. Move the control all the way up.'

[490:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And then move this keyframe as much as needed. Okay, if I just symmetrize this bone,'

[490:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'copy this driver, paste it into the dot r counterpart, and make it be driven by the dot R bone. Then we\'ll have the opposite side set'

[490:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up. Okay, now this big mouth bone is special. So, just leave it aside, but try to set up the remaining controls yourself. They just need to move in a single direction and they control'

[491:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exactly the shape that they\'re close to. I recorded the whole process of me setting up all of these controls, but I don\'t think it\'s going to be very useful to you. So, I\'ll just show you what I did.'

[491:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I did set up all of these controls and most of them, the lips ones, the smear, the squint, the eye blink, and the brow squeeze are set up exactly as the upper lip up control, which means that each'

[491:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one drives a single shape key and it drives it using its Y value. So, for example, for the lower lip down, if I open the driver editor,'

[491:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I can use the search here, by the way, to filter my drivers. So, if I look at the lower lip down driver, I\'m driving it using a bone with a similar name. It\'s this bone using its Y location in'

[491:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'local space. And the expression is simply var. And that is because I flipped my bones so that they are oriented in the'

[492:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'direction they are supposed to move. If your bones weren\'t flipped and they\'re pointing in the opposite direction, then you may have to set your expression to minus var, for example, but I don\'t need to.'

[492:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, so it\'s the same for all of these other controls that move in a single direction. The brows are slightly more complicated. Moving this control up activates the inner brow up and moving'

[492:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it down activates inner brow down. So, this is very similar to the mouth corner with the smile and frown. In the mouth corner, we also have a wide. So, the brows are similar to the mouth corner,'

[492:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'but slightly less complicated. But, if we look at the brows inner up, you\'ll see that they\'re driven by the'

[492:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'inner brow bone, which is this one. And the expression is var. And if we look at the inner brow down, they\'re driven by the same bone, same axis and local space. The only difference is that the expression is minus var. So, that'

[493:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'moving this control down will activate this shape key. And it\'s the same for the other brow control. And I also locked any axis that I don\'t want to use for these controls.'

[493:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And I also gave them a limit location constraint with affect transforms and owner set to local space. And then I just set the necessary minimum and maximum values so that the controls do'

[493:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not leave their intended space. Okay, now let\'s set up the mouth control and it is supposed to drive the mouth narrow shape. I\'m going to use the local X scale axis'

[493:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to drive this shape. So, let\'s lock Y and Z. And also add limit scale to this bone. Activate all limits and affect transform and switch to local space. And for limit'

[493:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scale, we have to set maximum to one because the default scale is always one. And I want to scale this bone to about 0.5 and that should trigger the mouth narrow shape. So, let\'s set minimum to'

[494:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '0.5. Now, it\'s just a matter of setting up the driver. Find mouth narrow, right click, add'

[494:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'driver. Object is armature and the bone will be SK mouth. We\'re going to use X scale in local space. Now here the expression will be'

[494:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'slightly more complicated. Again, the default scale value is one, so in the default state of the bone, we get the full shape key. This is definitely not what we want. To invert the value of one, I can change the'

[494:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'expression to 1 minus var. This sets the default value to zero. And as I scale this bone down to about 0.5, it will become 1 minus 0.5, so 0.5. So it is triggering the shape key, but'

[495:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not all the way. Let\'s go back to the driver. So we\'ll place this expression in parentheses and multiply it by two. That way when I reach the scale of 0.5, it will be multiplied by two, which is'

[495:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. So now just pressing the S key creates this shape. Just for fun, I\'ll create some additional shapes for the mouth. So let\'s go to the face, create a new'

[495:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shape key and call it mouth left. And I\'ll select the whole mouth, enable proportional editing,'

[495:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and here disable mirror. I want to move the mouth to the side like this. We may want to sculpt it a little bit as'

[496:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well. Okay, so this gives us this sideways'

[496:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'movement of the mouth. Now here is another way to mirror a shape key. I\'m going to have the mouth left activated and everything else set to zero. Create a new shape from mix, which'

[496:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'creates a copy of mouth left. Set this to zero, and let\'s call this one mouth right. Set it to one. Then select mouth right, go to this menu, and mirror the shape key. And that will give me mouth right. There'

[496:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is this vertex which probably wasn\'t quite symmetrical, so I\'ll just smooth it a little bit. And that is mouth right now. I\'ll create one more shape.'

[496:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Call it mouth up. And in edit mode, I\'ll move the whole mouth area, or the lips, up. Sculpt it a bit.'

[497:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And now let\'s set range min for mouth up to minus one. And this should work for our mouth'

[497:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'downs. So, let\'s name this shape mouth up down. And set the value to zero. Now I can make this mouth control control these additional mouth shapes. So, I\'ll unlock its X and Y location'

[497:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'values. And I\'ll have to set the maximum X to 0.01 or so, and also the Y. And the minimum to minus 0.01.'

[497:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now I can move this control within these limits. Let\'s add drivers. Mouth left will be driven by the'

[498:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'SK mouth bone. X location makes sense for left and right, and Y location for the up and down movement.'

[498:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Space to local space. And I\'ll just multiply this expression by 100 because my maximum movement value is 0.01, multiplying by 100 will give me'

[498:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a value of exactly one. So now moving this control left creates the mouth left expression. Let\'s copy this driver,'

[498:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'paste it into mouth right, and edit this expression to be minus var multiplied by 100. And this gives us this mouth movement'

[499:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you often see in facial motion capture. Let\'s paste the driver into mouth up down as well. This time we want the Y location in'

[499:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'local space to drive the control. And this sets it up right away. Now I think the full shape key is a'

[499:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'little bit too extreme for this semi-realistic character. So I\'m going to change the expression for mouth up down to var multiplied by 80 or so. So this shape can be triggered'

[499:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'only up to 80%. Okay, this made the tutorial a little bit longer again, but I think we managed to learn some cool new tricks. I really want this to be the one tutorial that you can just watch and you\'ll know all'

[499:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there is to know about shape keys. Here I decided to tweak the weight paint around the mouth just a little bit. You'

[500:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really need to test how the different shape keys interact with each other and also how the bone deformations on the jaw combine with the shape keys. And you may need to tweak the weight paint a a or the shapes a little bit to get the'

[500:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exact shapes that you want. But I think even with this relatively limited number of shapes, this face is capable of achieving a lot of natural expressions, lip-sync, and so on. But at'

[500:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the same time, it is just a solid base that you can keep building upon. And you can add any shapes that you feel your character needs. And with that, you completed rigging isn\'t scary. I hope it has been a great'

